1. c4 {Welcome to Part 1 of my new repertoire series on the Neo-Catalan(or the Fianchetto English)!   For those who don’t know me, I’m Sam Shankland, an American Super-GM over 2700 and a longtime Chessable Author. I’ve done 8 courses here already, seven of which are on the opening. Having done a full 1. d4 repertoire for White in 3 parts, a Semi-Slav repertoire for Black against 1. d4, a repertoire against the English, Reti, and Sidelines, and Classical Sicilian and Berlin Repertoires for Black against 1. e4, there came a question of what to do next.   Chessable has covered almost every single strong mainline and has a course ready that has been done by a strong grandmaster, but I did notice that nobody had recommended a Neo-Catalan course yet, which surprised me since I regard it as a very serious opening, and a good way to try to fight for an advantage. For the most part, I have kept this course as unique as possible, trying not to transpose to any 1.d4 lines if I can help it. That said, there are some places where I strongly feel transposing to a 1.d4 position is the best option, and in those cases, I did not hesitate to do so. The Neo-Catalan is based on opening with 1. c4, and then following up with 2. g3 against more or less any legal move. There are some obvious exceptions, such as if Black plays 1... b6 to get to the long diagonal first, or if he does something outlandish and ridiculous like 1... d5 or 1... h5, but for the most part, g2-g3 is our second move.   While some English repertoires do exist on Chessable, it would be foolish to think that they necessarily have anything to do with one another. Imagine that instead of playing 1. c4, you meet 1. e4 with 1... c5. You are now in the Sicilian. And the Najdorf, the Dragon, the Classical, the Taimanov, the Sveshnikov, the Four Knights... these all have some overlapping themes, but are entirely unique openings.   Similarly, opening with 1. c4 can be done in a huge variety of ways, and there has not been a dedicated 1. c4 and 2. g3 repertoire properly covered anywhere in a very long time. The whole point of more or less any g3/Bg2 system for White is to argue that our bishop on the long diagonal will be better than the Black counterpart on c8. When used successfully, White often gets slightly better positions with nagging pressure that will remain for a long time and with little to no risk, or if Black tries something concrete to try to immediately solve the problems, if anything goes wrong for him, it will go very wrong. There is a lot of appeal to playing this way, and more or less every 2700+ of the last 50 years has at some point tried to play a g3/Bg2 repertoire with White.   Once we have decided to play an opening with a kingside fianchetto, the next step is to choose which first move we will use. There are 3 shells you can fit this strategy into, and they all have pluses and minuses. The first option is to open with 1. Nf3 and 2. g3 in the style of the Reti. Of all of the options, I find this one the least convincing. The biggest reason is that I dislike that Black can push d7-d5 without having to play c7-c6 or e7-e6 first. This means he can aim to occupy the entire center with c5, Nc6, and e5, and it also becomes much harder for us to push c2-c4 through. Not only can Black take it and make it harder for us to get away with it, but he also can often play d5-d4, aiming for a reversed Benoni where he will not have had to play either e7-e6 or c7-c6, both of which don’t mesh well that particular plan.   The second option would be to build a repertoire based on 1. d4, 2. c4, and 3. g3 when allowed. This basic setup was first popularized by Boris Avrukh, who wrote some books for Quality Chess and recommended playing the Catalan and the Fianchetto King’s Indian and Grunfeld. However, there are some serious drawbacks to the 1. d4 move order. First of all, the Queen’s Gambit accepted exists, and White is certainly unable to bring the bishop to g2 there and have any hope of fighting for an edge.   The Slav also exists, against which I don’t particularly believe in a g2-g3 plan. Black will get his bishop to f5 or g4, and our pawn on d4 would be badly misplaced and better on d3- we will see this in our course. Within the King’s Indian and Grunfeld setups, I think committing to 1. d4 gives Black some extra options early on as well which significantly increases his chances of fighting for equality than they do in our repertoire where our d-pawn stays at home for some time. Within the Catalan setups, having committed to 1. d4 early in the game allows Black a better chance of being able to bolster his d5-pawn by allowing him the option of Bf8-b4+, provoking our bishop to the undesirable d2-square, where it is not only generally not a great piece but also blocks our knight from coming to d2. He also is able to take on c4 early and not let us take the pawn back right away, which produces reams upon reams of sharp theory where White has to remember tons of concrete moves in order to prove his compensation and continue to fight for an advantage.   The final option is to play 1. c4 and 2. g3, which was first proposed by Mihail Marin. He wrote an excellent 3 part series for Quality Chess in 2009-2010, which put this idea on the map. I think he did a fantastic job, but any opening repertoire series will become less and less relevant over time, and there are plenty of places in the books that did not stand the test of time, and where I want to do something very different, potentially very early in the game. The pluses of playing with 1. c4 and 2. g3 are enormous. I think this course will do a very good job of showing why a 1. c4 move order is desirable compared to 1. d4.   Literally ALL of the above problems immediately vanish, and I think our repertoire is strictly superior to a 1. d4 move order in every single one of these lines. The Queen's Gambit Accepted does not exist. The Slav allows us to play with Bg2 and the pawn coming to d3 instead of d4 in a lot of cases. Black’s options are seriously limited in Catalan setups and we can always transpose to a 1. d4 line whenever we want while completely eliminating any hope of dxc4 and hanging onto the pawn or an early Bb4+ and Be7, plus I have found ways to pressure Black’s position without transposing back to 1. d4 lines. We can take advantage of avoiding 1. d4 to avoid some of Black’s best lines in the Fianchetto Grunfeld and King’s Indian before ultimately pushing d2-d4 anyway and forcing him into an inferior version.   And perhaps most importantly, we have consistency on our side, as it is very, very rare that we ever have to do anything on move 2 other than g2-g3. There are a couple of spots in the random sidelines here, but after the very first chapter, for the remainder of this course and all subsequent courses, 2. g3 will be our move. This keeps the repertoire extremely consistent and gives us a lot of confidence that in any given game we decide to play it, the character of the position will be exactly what we expect it to be.   Based on all this, one might ask, why on earth would anyone ever choose a 1. d4 move order if they want to play a g3/Bg2 setup? Well, there are 3 reasons. The smallest of them is that playing d4 on the first move completely kills any hope Black has of pushing d5-d4 and taking the game into reversed Benoni territory. While I think that is a pretty strong argument that 1. d4 could be a better move order than 1. Nf3, I find it less problematic for us, since we already have established that a reversed Benoni is less enticing for Black when he must push e7-e6 or c7-c6 to get d7-d5 in.   The two big reasons that White could prefer a 1.d4 move order, however, are very notable. They are that 1. c4 allows black to play either 1... c5 or 1... e5, moves that 1. d4 neatly disallows and that contain plenty of challenges of their own. These will probably each comprise courses of their own, as I don’t think I will be able to fit both into one. Most of the strongest players who regularly go for g3 and Bg2 setups are able to play both 1. d4 and 1. c4 move orders. This is of course the best solution, keeping our opponents guessing. But, for players who are adding such a setup to their repertoire for the first time, I strongly believe 1. c4 is the better option. This is evidenced by the fact that whenever a top player who has shown a strong preference for 1. e4 in the past is trying to branch out into g3/Bg2 setups, they nearly always choose 1. c4. Svidler, Karjakin, and Dominguez are perfect examples.   One thing I have always hated is when someone writes a book on an opening and makes comments like “It is less important to know the concrete moves here and more important to know the ideas.” Even many years ago, I was very suspicious of such statements, but in today’s era, this is an absolute load of nonsense. There are no remotely decent openings in chess that can be properly learned with only memorization, and there are no remotely decent openings in chess that can be properly learned with only understanding. You absolutely need both.   That being said, every repertoire has some balance that must be struck, and this one certainly sways more towards the understanding side than the side of the concrete move. This is evidenced by the fact that it has the fewest trainable variations of any of my LTRs here on Chessable, but it has the most words!   As such, for this course, I think it is extremely important to purchase the video to go along with the move trainer. I did my best work with the video on all of my other courses as well, and I do believe it adds a lot of value to them, but it is not nearly as critical in any of my other work as it is in this course. I did my best to explain everything as well as I could in the text, but there’s only so much I can do on a written medium. A huge part of this repertoire is understanding our move orders and why we choose them, and I will constantly have to reset the position to the beginning, show a different move order perhaps even from move 1 of the game or even flip the board to see a similar positions with colors reversed, and show why it is different and does not work as well, and why 1. c4 and the following moves we make are best. This is critically important to understanding the repertoire, and just can’t be done proper justice with text alone.   With all that in mind, let’s get working! I broke the repertoire into 4 parts, and I’ve always believed in covering them in order from easiest to hardest. The first part is covering early sidelines, the second part covers g6/Bg7 systems, the third part covers Black playing e6 and d5 in the style of the Queen’s Gambit, and the final part covers Black playing c6 and d5 in the style of the Slav. Sections 2-4 have their own introductions as well, which explain some important themes and basic move orders that should be understood, especially concerning why we are starting with 1. c4, why I like starting with it more than 1. d4, and how that changes the way the game plays out. Happy studying!•1.d4d52.c4e62...dxc4We cannot put the bishop on g2 here!3.Nf3Nf64.g3Bb4+!The possibility of this move gives Black a very solid option in the proper Catalan that we can neatly avoid.•1.d4d52.c4e63.Nf3Nf64.g3dxc4!As well here, we cannot get the pawn back right away the way we can in a 1. c4 move order.5.Bg2Now, Black has 7 (!) serious ways to try to hang on to the pawn, all of which require very, very deep knowledge for White to hope to fight for an edge, all of which involve quite a bit of risk from White's side, and four of which are probably good enough for equality when you dig really deeply with modern engines.5...Bb4+,5...b5,5...c6,5...a6,5...Bd7,5...c5,5...Nbd7•1.d4Nf62.c4g63.Nf3Bg74.g3c65.Bg2d56.O-OO-O7.b3Because we have committed to d2-d4, I believe Black equalizes easily with either dxc4 followed by c7-c5 or the simple Bc8-f5. With a 1. c4 move order, the pawn being back on d2 is very helpful for us in both cases.7...Bf57...dxc48.bxc4c5•1.Nf3d5Whenever we play c4, the moves d5xc4 and d5-d4 become much more venomous than they would be if Black had to push e7-e6 or c7-c6 before playing d7-d5.} 
1. c5 {This and1...e5are the two major drawbacks to a 1. c4 repertoire based on Bg2 compared to a 1. d4 repertoire based on Bg2. These two responses will be covered in the second part of the course. I still find that this is nicer than allowing the options we'd have to cover in a 1. d4 move order.} 
