1. c4 {The somewhat non-forcing nature of playing c4 on the first move means that Black has a bit more freedom to play something offbeat than he would against e4 or d4. Moves like 1... b6 become sort of reasonable, and we should make sure to cover the sidelines properly. Still, I don't find them too challenging, and I think we can knock them all out in one section.} 
1. b6 {This move is not totally unreasonable, and Nikita Vitiugov once played it against me in a critical last-round game in the fight for first place in the 2020 Prague Masters. I won the game, but not without some serious mistakes early on!   In general, this move makes a lot of sense against us because we are not as fast to try to take the whole center, and g2-g3 is unappealing when Black can get his bishop to b7 before we can get ours to g2.} 
2. d4 {This is another spot where I really think the best option by far is to go back into 1. d4 territory, and we will transpose directly into the English Defense. I was quite satisfied with the analysis I did in part 1 of my 1. d4 course and I think I put Black's position under a lot of pressure. I really have nothing further to add, so a simple copy/paste will do just fine.} 
2. e6
3. a3 {White's plan is to play Nc3 without having to worry about Bb4, much like one would see in a Petrosian Queen's Indian. But this is a better version, as White has not yet committed his knight to f3.} 
3. Bb7
4. Nc3 {Now, if White is allowed to play e2-e4, he will have a very nice edge. Black should stop him, either with Nf6 or f5. But both moves are met with the same response.} 
4. Nf6
5. d5 {White takes extra space in the center and blunts the b7-bishop. They look pleasantly better to me.} 
5. Bd6
6. Nf3 {It is best to start with this move before g2-g3 to avoid letting Black put his bishop on e5.} 
6. O-O
7. g3 {White is ready to complete his development with Bg2 and O-O, and I can't really see anything fun for Black to do. He will suffer with less space. Since he did not play f7-f5, he does not have any active plans connected with a knight jumping to e4. So, his position looks miserable.} 
7. c6 {This looks like the most natural try, but it doesn't do much.} 
8. Bg2 {It turns out that Black cannot comfortably capture on d5.} 
8. cxd5
9. cxd5 {And now Black could take exd5, but his extra pawn would be meaningless, likely to fall, and his coordination would be terrible. But he cannot take with pieces either.} 
9. exd5 {This is the recommendation of Yuriy Krykun in his course here on Chessable. It may be the best move, but it definitely does not equalize.} 
10. O-O
10. Na6 {Black will make some attempt to hang onto this extra pawn. Now, Krykun only examines Nd4 and Nh4 - natural moves that attempt to win the pawn back. He does not mention the following powerful idea.} 
11. Nb5 {White couldn't care less about the pawn down - the doubled isolanis on the d-file only hinder Black's development and don't do anything useful for him.} 
11. Be7
12. b4
12. Nc7
13. Nxc7
13. Qxc7
14. Nd4 {The computer only gives White a small edge, but it looks like a miserable position for Black to my human eye. Bb2, Rc1, Qb3 - White's position plays itself, and his coordination is perfect. Black's bishop on b7 is extremely sad. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here.} 
