1. c4 {The somewhat non-forcing nature of playing c4 on the first move means that Black has a bit more freedom to play something offbeat than he would against e4 or d4. Moves like 1... b6 become sort of reasonable, and we should make sure to cover the sidelines properly. Still, I don't find them too challenging, and I think we can knock them all out in one section.} 
1. f5 {With this move, Black is advertising his desire to play some version of the Dutch Defense. In general, the Dutch is a pretty shaky opening, but it does have one clear merit of putting a lot of pressure on the e4-square. I think our pawn being back on d2 and having the potential to go to d3 instead takes a lot of sting out of Black's position.} 
2. g3 {As usual, we play g2-g3 on the second move. Now, I really think Black will want to push e7-e5 at some point, taking the game into 1...e5 territory that we will see in a future course. But, let's see what happens if he tries to firmly keep the game in Dutch territory and avoid 1...e5 at all moments.} 
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. e6
4. Nf3
4. Be7 {Continuing in the style of the Classical Dutch doesn't help either.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O
6. Nc3
6. d5 {Aiming to transpose back to a Stonewall does not inspire confidence either. After6...d6we just take queenside space.7.b4!?e58.d3⩲White is a tempo up on a position we will see in the 1... e5 course. He has the same easy plan as always - Bc1-b2, b4-b5, keep gaining queenside space.} 
7. cxd5
7. exd5
8. d3 {Just like we saw against the more normal Stonewall setup where Black put the bishop on d6, White will aim for the e2-e4 advance. The only difference is that here, we should make sure to play Qd1-c2 first to make sure not to allow the exchange of queens.} 
8. c6
9. Qc2 {Black's position does not make much sense to me. He lacks any active prospects with his bishop on e7 instead of d6, and sooner or later e2-e4 will come. White can even consider playing it slowly with b2-b3, Bc1-b2, etc, and only executing e2-e4 later. In general, Black's position looks miserable.} 
