5. d4 {In general, I am loathed to transpose back into a 1. d4 line if I can help it. But, here, I do think this is far and away White's best option, and I could not find any other way to try to put Black's position under any pressure.   That said, we are in a very specific line within 1. d4, where we got to play a g3/Bg2 setup against the King's Indian, and where Black lost his chance to play anything involving d7-d5. Furthermore, I am suggesting a clever move order that reduces some of Black's options.} 
5. d6 {This is the main move by far, and will probably be almost automatic for a King's Indian player.} 
6. h3 {I quite like this very rare move, which has been seen less than 1% of the time that this position has been reached. Of course, 6. Nf3 is overwhelmingly the most popular move, with 6. e3 and Nge2 to follow the second most popular. My point is simple. I will ask Black to make one more move, and only then decide where my g1-knight belongs.   I tried it twice myself in the goofy Halloween mask blitz tournament against Gawain Jones. While the match did not go my way, that can be chalked up to hanging a rook in one move in a winning endgame; the opening went quite well.6.e3This move is possible, but I am not a huge fan. I believe Black has a very specific plan which guarantees him a fine position.6...e57.Nge2Re8This is the setup Black should aim for, and he can go ahead and play e5-e4 sooner rather than later. He is ready for c7-c6 and d6-d5, and White's misplaced knight on e2 not only makes it harder to challenge the e4-pawn than it otherwise would be on d2, but also critically weakens the light squares around his king. I think Black is totally fine. While I do not like this position for White, I will be very happy to set up with e3 and Nge2 if Black commits to something that is not consistent with this plan.} 
6. c5 {This would be a very natural move for Black, counterattacking in the center, and it was Jones' choice against me. Of course, we should not take blitz games very seriously, but it is good to know what the raw instinct of a strong and devoted KID player is when he does not have time to really think it over.} 
7. e3 {Now we see the point. White has provoked Black into advancing c7-c5, which is completely out of place for his best plan against the e2-e3 and Ng1-e2 setup.} 
7. cxd4 {7...Nc6, Gawain Jones' recommendation, is analyzed here.} 
8. exd4 {Now, White has a very simple plan - Nge2 and O-O. Should he pull this off, he is probably going to be better. With the bishop on g2 pressuring Black's queenside, the only real hope for counterplay I can see is to try to play e7-e5 and Nb8-c6.} 
8. e5 {I took on e5 against Jones here, which is fine and leads to a nice endgame, but I don't see a huge reason not to stick with Nge2, since 8...Nc6 would force that position anyway.} 
9. Nge2 {9.dxe5After trading on d8 and Bg5 comes next, White should be a little better here as well.} 
9. Nc6 {Now, Black is threatening to take on d4. So we defend it.} 
10. Be3 {White will be clearly better if he can castle next. Qd2, Rfd1, Rac1, the position basically plays itself. Black needs to be extremely direct to put up any kind of fight.} 
10. exd4
11. Nxd4
11. Nxd4 {11...Bd712.Ndb5±Black is strategically in horrible shape thanks to his weak d6-pawn and White's fantastic pieces.} 
12. Bxd4
12. Re8+
13. Kf1 {But even still, I like White's position. He will castle by hand with Kf1-g1-h2. This is a bit slow, but I don't think Black can really hurt him in the meantime, and long term I like the better structure. This line is analyzed in greater detail here.} 
