7. Nf3 {Now and only now, we go for Ng1-f3. Again, we are back in mainline Fianchetto King's Indian territory, but in a very specific version. By forcing Black to push e7-e5 so quickly, we have avoided tons of plans, including but not limited to c6 and Qa5, c6 and Bf5, c5, the Panno with Nc6 a6 and Rb8, and who knows how many more ways Black can set up his pieces.} 
7. Nbd7 {This setup has long been popular for Black in blitz games, owing to the easy nature of how to play the position. He takes on d4, plays Re8, Nc5, c6, sits with little space, waits for you to burn your time and overextend, and tricks you somehow. Anyone who has ever played the White side of the Fianchetto King's Indian surely knows this to be true. Additionally, if this is the setup that Black decides he wants, there are no move order tricks of any kind that White can use to avoid it. That said, objectively speaking, White is clearly better.   Now, I think one of the biggest reasons that White players can get frustrated by this line is that even though they know that they are better, based on the current state of theory, it feels like you have to put your pieces on completely different squares depending on what Black does. And just when you think you've memorized them all, someone comes up with a new move for Black that certainly does not equalize, but you need to know a new piece assortment... one thing I have discovered in the last several years is that people can come up with and spew out new BS ideas much, much faster than I can check and refute new BS ideas. So, I decided to put a lot of effort into this position and see if I could find a way for White to set up his pieces so that he really does not have to remember much, and I am satisfied with what I found.   To begin with, we will play e2-e4, O-O and Rf1-e1 against more or less any legal move. Having our first three moves pre-determined helps a lot! Then, the most critical part of understanding the position is knowing what to do with the dark-squared bishop. In general, I believe its best square is e3. But, for the most part, I think we cannot get it there without allowing counterplay in a lot of lines. So, the following guide is important in understanding where the bishop wants to go.   1. In general, our default option is that we will want to play b3 and Bb2. Black can stop this plan by pre-emptively playing a7-a5, making sure to meet b2-b3 with a5-a4.   2. If he does not play a7-a5, we will play b2-b3. Then, should a7-a5 come, we should spend a move on Ra1-b1 before playing Bc1-b2, making sure that we can meet a5-a4 with b2-b4 without a4-a3 coming in response.   3. If Black plays a7-a5 before we can play b2-b3, then we will play Nd4-b5, taking advantage of the weakened b5-square. The bishop will then be fantastic on f4, and can come back to e3 if it is ever kicked by Nf6-h5.   4. If Black ever puts his d7-knight on e5, we usually can aim for maximum punishment and put the bishop on e3. The biggest drawback of the bishop going to e3 is that Black can attack the e4-pawn with some combination of Nd7-c5 and Rf8-e8, and this is not a thing anymore once the knight goes to e5.} 
8. e4 {I like starting with e2-e4. This disallows some trickery with Nd7-b6.8.O-Oexd49.Nxd4Nb6This line is not amazing for Black, but I see no reason to allow it and burden our memory even further.} 
8. c6 {Once upon a time, the plan involving leaving the pawn on e5 and playing some kind of Qd8-b6 had some merit to it. In modern times, the machines just laugh. Black should stick to taking on d4 and putting the knight on c5.} 
9. O-O
9. Qa5 {This move is a little tricky, but nothing to be scared of. As always, we respond the same way.} 
10. Re1 {I can't begin to express how nice it is to always play the same few moves no matter what Black does in a position that has been seen 10,000 times. The machines give this as third best. Now that e4 is overprotected, we are ready for d4-d5 next. Furthermore, clearing the f1 square makes it easier to defend c4.} 
10. exd4 {10...Nb611.Bf1!±Black is totally out of steam and has no plan to increase the pressure any further.} 
11. Nxd4
11. Ne5 {This is the only logical follow-up for Black.} 
12. Bf1 {It's nice that this move is legal. Now, when applying the guidelines of the original reasoning, we note that since Black has played Nd7-e5, now our bishop does indeed belong on its best square, e3.} 
12. Qb6 {This is probably Black's best try, but I don't think much of it.} 
13. Be3
13. Qc7
14. f4 {Black's knight is forced back to d7, he has lost a ton of time and White reached perfect coordination. The machine claims White is already winning, and I do not think it is exaggerating. The bishops will sit on f2 and g2, White will play Qd2 and Rad1, and Black's position will collapse.} 
