1. c4 {The somewhat non-forcing nature of playing c4 on the first move means that Black has a bit more freedom to play something offbeat than he would against e4 or d4. Moves like 1... b6 become sort of reasonable, and we should make sure to cover the sidelines properly. Still, I don't find them too challenging, and I think we can knock them all out in one section.} 
1. Nf6 {•1...g6This move might look like it is just destined to transpose back into the normal mainline King's Indian setups, but in fact it is quite a clever move order if Black wants to play with c7-c6 and d7-d5.2.g3Now, 2... e5 and 2... c5 transpose to what will be covered in future courses. If Black does not choose one of these options, I would be pretty surprised to see him do anything other than Bf8-g7 and Ng8-f6 on the next couple of moves.2...Bg73.Bg2c64.Nf3d55.O-ONf66.b3!transposes to the 2... c6 move order.•1...g62.g3Bg73.Bg2Nf64.Nc3transposes to the mainline.•1...g62.g3Bg73.Bg2e5this will be covered in the1... e5 course.•1...g62.g3Bg73.Bg2e64.Nf3transposes to the 1... e6 section.} 
2. g3
2. g6 {2...d5This will not have an independent value.3.cxd5Nxd54.Bg2Now, c7-c5 will transpose to a position covered in the 1... c5 move order, e7-e5 will be covered in the 1... e5 move order, and g7-g6 transposes to the 2... g6 and 3... d5 move order. I don't see any other reasonable moves.3...Qxd54.Nf3Black should probably push e7-e5 here, leading to a position that will be covered in a future course via a 1... e5 move order. Still, I'd mention that White's best plan should hardly be considered rocket science.} 
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3 {Black has lost his chance to play for d7-d5 and is firmly in Fianchetto King's Indian territory.} 
4. O-O {• This should be preferred. After4...d65.d4I don't think Black has any serious alternatives to O-O, transposing to the mainline.•4...c5transposes to the Symmetrical English, which will be covered in the second course.•4...e5This transposes to a 1... e5 line that will also be covered in the second course.} 
5. d4 {In general, I am loathed to transpose back into a 1. d4 line if I can help it. But, here, I do think this is far and away White's best option, and I could not find any other way to try to put Black's position under any pressure.   That said, we are in a very specific line within 1. d4, where we got to play a g3/Bg2 setup against the King's Indian, and where Black lost his chance to play anything involving d7-d5. Furthermore, I am suggesting a clever move order that reduces some of Black's options.} 
5. d6 {This is the main move by far, and will probably be almost automatic for a King's Indian player.} 
6. h3 {I quite like this very rare move, which has been seen less than 1% of the time that this position has been reached. Of course, 6. Nf3 is overwhelmingly the most popular move, with 6. e3 and Nge2 to follow the second most popular. My point is simple. I will ask Black to make one more move, and only then decide where my g1-knight belongs.   I tried it twice myself in the goofy Halloween mask blitz tournament against Gawain Jones. While the match did not go my way, that can be chalked up to hanging a rook in one move in a winning endgame; the opening went quite well.6.e3This move is possible, but I am not a huge fan. I believe Black has a very specific plan which guarantees him a fine position.6...e57.Nge2Re8This is the setup Black should aim for, and he can go ahead and play e5-e4 sooner rather than later. He is ready for c7-c6 and d6-d5, and White's misplaced knight on e2 not only makes it harder to challenge the e4-pawn than it otherwise would be on d2, but also critically weakens the light squares around his king. I think Black is totally fine. While I do not like this position for White, I will be very happy to set up with e3 and Nge2 if Black commits to something that is not consistent with this plan.} 
6. e5 {This move feels very thematic for a King's Indian player. It also forces us away from the e2-e3 plan, since unlike what we saw after6...c5, this is consistent with Black's best response.6...c67.e4!White takes all the central space and is ready for Ng1-e2 next, with a fantastic position.} 
7. Nf3 {Now and only now, we go for Ng1-f3. Again, we are back in mainline Fianchetto King's Indian territory, but in a very specific version. By forcing Black to push e7-e5 so quickly, we have avoided tons of plans, including but not limited to c6 and Qa5, c6 and Bf5, c5, the Panno with Nc6 a6 and Rb8, and who knows how many more ways Black can set up his pieces.} 
