1. c4 {The somewhat non-forcing nature of playing c4 on the first move means that Black has a bit more freedom to play something offbeat than he would against e4 or d4. Moves like 1... b6 become sort of reasonable, and we should make sure to cover the sidelines properly. Still, I don't find them too challenging, and I think we can knock them all out in one section.} 
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. We will return on this strategy starting here.   Now, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. d4 {One of the best ways for Black to attempt to punish us for playing the English is to immediately point out that we might regret not having a pawn on d4. Indeed, this would be a fourth strategy for how to fight for equality in the Catalan that does not exist within a 1. d4 move order.   Still, this idea highlights one of the biggest reasons that I chose to do an English repertoire and not a Reti. By starting with c2-c4 on move 1, we make it impossible for Black to push d7-d5-d4 without first playing c7-c6 or e7-e6, as he has done here. Once a Benoni structure is reached, it should be pretty clear that the pawn on e6 would rather be on e5.} 
4. Nf3
4. Nf6
5. O-O {Now, Black's most common and most principled move is c7-c5. This will take the game into a Benoni structure where White is effectively up 2 tempi because 1. He is White and got the first move and 2. Black has played e7-e6 rather than e7-e5. However, this does not necessarily guarantee an advantage. Being 2 tempi up on a bad position is an improvement, but how much does it change the evaluation? I think White is on the more comfortable side of equality and can force Black to find some good moves.} 
5. c5
6. e3
6. Nc6
7. exd4
7. cxd4
8. d3 {Now, it is a well-known rule that when playing against the Benoni, you want to avoid piece exchanges. So, Black should not be thrilled about allowing Bc1-g5. But, I don't think he has much of a choice.} 
8. Bd6 {8...Be7?!is too passive.9.Na3O-O10.Re1⩲White prevents e6-e5 forcefully, and he is ready for Na3-c2 next. In general, when you play Na3-c2, Black will be unable to prevent b2-b4 from coming by controlling the b4-square, and should instead be looking for counterplay with Bc8-f5 and bringing a knight to c5. Since the bishop cannot come to f5, White is in great shape.} 
9. Bg5
9. h6
10. Bxf6 {Intending Nbd2-Ne4 next.} 
10. Qxf6
11. Nbd2
11. Qe7 {I don't think Black should be allowing his bishop to be captured so easily. He is hoping to only allow one exchange of minor pieces.} 
12. Re1
12. O-O
13. a3
13. a5 {Now, White has tried a lot of different plans in this position, but there is a new modern one that appeals to me most.} 
14. Nb3 {White takes advantage of Black's pawn being back on e6, and attacks d4 directly.} 
14. Qf6 {What else?} 
15. c5
15. Bc7
16. Rc1 {White is ready to bring his knight back to d2 and then head to c4 or e4- its purpose on b3 was achieved, as he managed to carry out the c4-c5 advance. My computer absolutely screams equal, showing zeroes upon zeroes after more or less every move.   In my human estimation, Black's position is unpleasant - after all, we know what to think whenever a computer calls a Benoni structure equal! White's score in human practice from this position has been tremendous, albeit with a small sample size.} 
