6. c5 {This is a very direct move and a natural attempt to equalize. White is in a somewhat awkward spot for my repertoire since the more or less automatic looking Bc1-b2 would allow d5-d4, when White does not get to play my early Ne5 idea. So, we should resolve the tension right away.} 
7. cxd5 {I like this direct move, and I think it is a bad sign for Black that the machine wants to take back with the pawn.} 
7. exd5 {7...Nxd5Despite the computer's indifference between the recaptures on d5, I feel pretty strongly that this is Black's best try to fight for equality. I don't believe in the structure for him after exd5 instead. This line is analyzed in greater detail starting from here.} 
8. d4 {No matter what the computers say, I never really believe that Black can equalize playing a Tarrasch setup without immediately provoking some kind of conflict. The bishop on g2 exerts such strong pressure upon the soon to be isolated d5-pawn, and the kingside formation really makes any hope for counterplay pretty meager.   White has a very simple plan - Bb2 and Nc3. If he can make these two developing moves without anything happening to him in the meantime, he will be clearly better.} 
8. Nc6 {8...Ne49.Bb2Nc6transposes to the mainline in Chapter4.} 
9. Bb2
9. Bg4 {Simple development will not do for Black.} 
10. dxc5
10. Bxc5
11. Nc3 {White has a nice advantage due to the isolated d-pawn, and can follow up with Ra1-c1 next. The question is not whether he is better, the question is how much.} 
