6. d4 {This seems like a very reasonable time for Black to try to transition the position into some kind of Benoni, arguing that b2-b3 is not the most useful move for White in this structure. I think it is probably his best move, and maybe one of his best lines on the whole in this entire repertoire. He surely should be fine objectively, but I did some digging on a new-ish idea that I think contains some venom.} 
7. e3
7. c5 {Until recently, White had taken on d4 in nearly every game to reach this position. He should have a fantastic reversed Benoni, but it is a Benoni all the same. He certainly is not worse and has reasonable chances to play a complicated game, and I even lost on the black side of this position once to Hari (Pentala Harikrishna, Chessable Note) back when I was 2650. But, for this repertoire, I prefer something a little fresher.} 
8. Ne5 {I like this move a lot, highlighting that Black is further behind in development than he would like to be. Normally in a Benoni, you should not be able to occupy this square so easily. White's goal is to bolster his knight with f2-f4 if needed, and he is always happy to trade a pair of pieces.} 
8. Qc7 {The machine is pretty agnostic here, not seeing much difference in evaluation between Qd8-c7 and some knight to d7 instead. But, I am very confident that this is Black's best move.8...Nfd7should not have much independent value and is covered here.8...Nbd7feels very human to me and is covered here.} 
9. f4 {White bolsters the knight. This is the line where it becomes clear why it is important to wait on capturing d4. It's nice that we never have to worry about the option going away since d4xe3 always leaves Black with an awful position.} 
9. Nbd7 {9...dxe3?10.dxe3±White's pieces spring to life now that the d4-pawn is no longer restricting them, and Black is much worse thanks to the activity of White's powerful bishops.} 
10. Nd3 {Now, White has a very simple plan. He will play Nb1-a3, probably forcing Black to burn a tempo on a7-a6. Then, the knight comes back to c2, and the bishop comes to b2, and Black will struggle to keep the center under control. The f2-f4 advance makes it much harder to stay solid because e6-e5 obviously opens up some dynamic possibilities.10.exd4?Taking on d4 gives Black a lot more possibilities that I am really hoping to avoid.10...cxd411.Nd3e5!This is the clearest example. White is not really able to continue along as if nothing happened, as now e5-e4 is a serious threat.12.Bb2e4!13.Nf2With pawns remaining on e3 and c5 here, Black would be busted. As is, he can take advantage of both absences quite ruthlessly.13...e3!14.Nd3Nc5!-+} 
10. e5 {I think Black absolutely has to grab the bull by the horns here and create a crisis in the center. Slow moves will not cut it.} 
11. Bb2 {White is ready for the same plan of Nb1-a3-c2. Should he execute it safely, he will be much better. Black has to be very precise to maintain a playable position.} 
11. Bd6 {11...e4?This move would work beautifully for Black if we had already exchanged on d4. But, since we haven't, following12.Nf2±he is missing the move e4-e3, and his center collapses immediately. White should win at least a pawn.} 
12. Na3
12. a6 {Of course Black cannot allow the knight to reach b5.} 
13. Nc2 {Now, White has a very simple idea. Take on e5, then take on d4, winning a pawn. In fact, Black is actually unable to stop him! He needs to be very precise to play for compensation.} 
13. Re8 {The best move. Black accepts that he will probably lose a pawn and looks to let his pieces spring to life when this happens.13...dxe3?14.Nxe3+-Similarly here, Black is dead lost thanks to White's huge advantage in activity. I guess the next move could be Ne3-f5.} 
14. fxe5 {I don't see a great way to delay this move or play patiently, so let's go for it.} 
14. Nxe5
15. Nxe5
15. Bxe5 {Now we see that while White wins the d4-pawn, Black's pieces can quickly jump to life and the rook on e8 makes perfect sense.} 
16. exd4 {Now, Black should be precise.} 
16. Bg4 {16...cxd4?I could easily see a human doing this.17.Qf3!±White's queen finds a fantastic square, and Black's bishop is prevented from coming to g4. Ra1-e1 comes next and Black is in big trouble.} 
17. Bf3
17. Bxf3
18. Qxf3
18. cxd4
19. Ne1 {The machine spears that this position is absolutely equal, and offers an evaluation of 0.00 after more or less every legal move. A big part of modern preparation is looking for positions like this one and trying to use human judgment to decide whether it truly feels equal or not.   Of course, in a higher chess sense, Black has to be fine if the computer is this insistent. But in my human estimation, White's position is easier to play with the rather obvious plan of Ne1-d3 and Ra1-e1, and there is certainly no route to a direct draw or any way to kill the game- we will still get to play.   Perhaps I am not objective and others will disagree, but I'd say the results of this opening are as good as we can reasonably expect against an opponent who was perfectly prepared and played the best moves through move 18.} 
