[Black "e6/d5 Setups: 3...Nf6 4.Nf3 dxc4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4 {The somewhat non-forcing nature of playing c4 on the first move means that Black has a bit more freedom to play something offbeat than he would against e4 or d4. Moves like 1... b6 become sort of reasonable, and we should make sure to cover the sidelines properly. Still, I don't find them too challenging, and I think we can knock them all out in one section.} 
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. We will return on this strategy starting here.   Now, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. Nf6
4. Nf3 {Now, this is Black's last moment to reasonably hope to capture on c4.} 
4. dxc4
5. Qa4+ {White takes back the pawn on c4 without allowing Black to attempt to defend it. Now, Black has a few options of how to get his pieces out.5.Na3?!This would be the move aiming for maximum punishment, hoping to take back with the knight on c4. It was also the recommendation of Mihail Marin in his original work for Quality Chess once upon a time, which has long been held up as the gold standard for the Fianchetto English. But, I don't think it stood the test of time too well. Black can take on a3 in one move, and he should be fine.5...Bxa36.bxa3b5!I don't think Black has much to complain about. He is ready for Bc8-b7 and can always plug the long diagonal with Nf6-d5 if needed. The machine even offers him some edge- he is up a pawn after all. White is not fast enough to generate a serious initiative.} 
5. Bd7 {This is a very solid move, but one that I have trouble believing will fully equalize in human terms.} 
6. Qxc4
6. c5 {Black hopes to play Bd7-c6 next, neutralizing the long diagonal. He should be fine if he pulls that off, but we will not let this happen so easily.6...Bc6This challenges the long diagonal, but at far too heavy a cost. Black will deeply regret blocking his c-pawn, which is almost never a good idea in d-pawn or c-pawn openings. You can find this line here.} 
7. Ne5
7. Qc8 {An important move. Black defends b7, and gets ready for Nc6 next. After7...Nc6?8.Nxc6±Black will end up with a horrific pawn structure.} 
8. O-O
8. Nc6
9. Nxd7
9. Qxd7 {After Bd7, this position should come very fast, and neither side really has any great alternatives. Both sides got what they want- Black has a solid position with no bad pieces and a little extra central space, and White took a very important bishop.   At first, the machine reads that White is pleasantly better, and then over time it slowly drops to a level very close to equality. This usually implies that the position is basically fine for Black, but it takes some moves and understanding to prove it. In general, I find White's position easier to play, and there is a typical plan that I really like and think you should know.} 
10. Nc3
10. Be7
11. d3
11. O-O
12. Qa4 {White has a simple plan. He wants to go Bd2, Rfc1, Rab1, and eventually push a2-a3. He has every chance of fighting for the b2-b4 break, and if he ever gets it, Black's position can become critical very fast as his space advantage will dissipate and White's bishops will spring to life. My computer is entirely unimpressed and calls the position equal, but in human terms, I much prefer White. He has a clear plan of action for the coming moves and is not running much risk. This line is analyzed in greater detail here.} 
