1. c4 {The somewhat non-forcing nature of playing c4 on the first move means that Black has a bit more freedom to play something offbeat than he would against e4 or d4. Moves like 1... b6 become sort of reasonable, and we should make sure to cover the sidelines properly. Still, I don't find them too challenging, and I think we can knock them all out in one section.} 
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. We will return on this strategy starting here.   Now, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. Nf6
4. Nf3 {Now, this is Black's last moment to reasonably hope to capture on c4.} 
4. dxc4
5. Qa4+ {White takes back the pawn on c4 without allowing Black to attempt to defend it. Now, Black has a few options of how to get his pieces out.5.Na3?!This would be the move aiming for maximum punishment, hoping to take back with the knight on c4. It was also the recommendation of Mihail Marin in his original work for Quality Chess once upon a time, which has long been held up as the gold standard for the Fianchetto English. But, I don't think it stood the test of time too well. Black can take on a3 in one move, and he should be fine.5...Bxa36.bxa3b5!I don't think Black has much to complain about. He is ready for Bc8-b7 and can always plug the long diagonal with Nf6-d5 if needed. The machine even offers him some edge- he is up a pawn after all. White is not fast enough to generate a serious initiative.} 
5. c6 {This move has seen some play too, and it has its merits. Unlike what we will see next chapter with Nb8-d7, Black doesn't leave anything up to chance and will clearly accomplish b7-b5 next, which speaks heavily in his favor. That said, he still will not fix his light squared bishop without pushing c6-c5 later, which will cost him a valuable tempo.} 
6. Qxc4
6. b5 {It would be really surprising for Black to play anything else, but I do feel that I should point out that it is important for him to push b7-b5 right away. The point is that when White plays d2-d4, the best place for him to retreat his queen to will be d3. By pushing b7-b5 directly, he attacks the queen at a moment when she does not have this option.} 
7. Qb3 {I think this is the best place for the queen to go. Now, the battle lines are drawn. As we saw in the Chapter 1 Introduction, Black should be very fine if he can use the time that White spent recapturing the c4-pawn to contest the long diagonal. Here, he got b7-b5 in directly before we had anything to say about it. But, this came at a price. c7-c6 not only cost him a valuable tempo, but it also means that he will not fully execute his equalizing plan until he can not only get the bishop to b7, but also push c6-c5 as well.   If White is able to fully prevent c6-c5 from coming, he should be much better and perhaps even close to strategically winning. If Black can push c6-c5 safely, he should be totally fine. Best play will lead to a result in the middle. But for now, the queen does a better job on b3 of trying to prevent the c6-c5 break than she would do on c2 because she is pressuring the b5-pawn.7.Qc2This would be the most consistent with playing Qc4-c2 against the same c7-c6 and b7-b5 plan without the knights coming to f3 and f6 first, but here I believe Black is quite fine. The reason is that after7...Bb78.a4The knight being committed to f3 already means that Black does not have to worry about a4xb5, and can ignore the 'threat' completely rather than make the weakening move b5-b4.8...Nbd7Black looks fine to me.} 
7. Bb7 {Nobody ever plays anything else.7...a6This is Black's second most common move, with a grand total of 4 games played. It will promptly transpose to the mainline.8.Ne5Bb79.O-ONbd710.d4} 
8. O-O
8. Nbd7 {In general, in all of the lines where Black is trying to take on c4 and get b5 in, he usually needs to leave the bishop on f8 for awhile and develop his queenside first.8...a69.Ne5Nbd710.d4transpose to the mainline.} 
9. d4
9. a6 {Now, Black is ready for c6-c5 to come next. If he is allowed to play it, he will surely equalize right away, and he will be happy to have not burned any time with his f8-bishop, as it can take back in one move without having to stop on e7 in between. If we want to keep him under pressure, we are forced into action right away.} 
10. Ne5 {The only testing move. White clears his knight off of the long diagonal, opening up the bishop on g2 to pin the c6-pawn. If White could stabilize this position and not allow Black to play c6-c5 on a permanent basis with no changes to the structure, he should be more or less winning. But, this move does allow Black to double the pawns in the center.} 
10. Qb6 {It is a testament to the danger of the line that even a player as strong as Hikaru chose this move in a classical game. It makes a lot of sense. Black overprotects c6 and defends the b7-bishop at the same time, allowing c6-c5 to come next. But, funnily enough, he is more or less busted already.} 
11. Nxd7 {Magnus played Bc1-e3, which was not bad and he did go on to win a game we will see in the annotated games section, but White can be more to the point.} 
11. Nxd7
12. Nc3 {I like this move a lot. There is no universe where Black can consider falling even further behind on development with Qb6xd4 and opening the d-file at the same time, and the knight on c3 turns out to be very good prophylaxis against c6-c5.12.Be3?!This is much less convincing.12...c5!13.d5exd5!I really dislike that we cannot take with the knight on d5.14.Bxd5Bxd515.Qxd5Rd8White might be a little better, but no more than that. We can cause so much more trouble than this!} 
12. c5 {This feels like a human move to me. After12...Qxd4?13.Be3White's huge lead in development is completely decisive.} 
13. Na4 {The point of Nb1-c3 is revealed.} 
13. Qa7 {13...bxa4?14.Qxb6Nxb615.Bxb7+-White is obviously winning this endgame.} 
14. Bxb7
14. Qxb7 {14...bxa415.Qf3!The only move, but an obvious and good one. With Bb7-c6 coming next, Black may as well resign. His king will perish in the center with all the open lines, and he is not even up material.} 
15. Nxc5
15. Nxc5
16. dxc5
16. Bxc5
17. Qc3 {Absolutely devastating. Black will need to tuck his bishop all the way back to f8 to avoid losing his whole kingside.  White should easily win the game with his active rooks coming to the d and c-files before Black can complete his development. The bishop having to go back to f8 is a real punch to the gut.} 
