1. c4 {The somewhat non-forcing nature of playing c4 on the first move means that Black has a bit more freedom to play something offbeat than he would against e4 or d4. Moves like 1... b6 become sort of reasonable, and we should make sure to cover the sidelines properly. Still, I don't find them too challenging, and I think we can knock them all out in one section.} 
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. We will return on this strategy starting here.   Now, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. dxc4 {This is Black's last reasonable opportunity to try to capture on c4.} 
5. Qa4+ {White takes back the pawn on c4 without allowing Black to attempt to defend it. Now, Black has a few options of how to get his pieces out.} 
5. Nbd7 {Thematically, this feels like the most principled move, and I believe it is the strongest one. Black brings out a new piece and does not block the long diagonal.} 
6. Qxc4 {Now, Black only has two serious moves.} 
6. c5 {This is considerably less common than a7-a6, but in my opinion, it is not a worse move. In the mainline with6...a7-a6,we see that after the accurate response7.Qc2!Black is still not able to push b5, and instead plays7...c5.By starting with c7-c5, Black is aiming to do something similar, but with a different move order. We have to react to this move very differently than we would react to a7-a6.} 
7. d3 {I like this move a lot. We do not need to move the queen just yet since Black was not threatening b7-b5, and overprotecting the queen on c4 serves as good prophylaxis against the more modest b7-b6 as well. Additionally, Black cannot play Ra8-b8 on pain of Bc1-f4.7.Qc2?This is cooperative. I wish I could recommend it so that we could stay consistent, but unfortunately here, Black is very fine.7...b6!8.Ne5?!Nd5!The point. Black would be facing devastating consequences after Ne5-c6 if his pawn were back on c7. As is, the queen has the c7-square, and White is already a little worse.7.O-O?!This also allows Black to take the long diagonal.7...b6!8.Nd4Ne59.Nc6Nxc410.Nxd8Nd5Black's knight is not hanging on c4 here, and in fact White should be precise to maintain the balance. This position highlights why I like starting with d2-d3.} 
7. a6 {This is a very natural move, but also one that creates a strategic flaw. Black wants to push b7-b5 next, and White should be careful not to let him. Then, Black will have to settle for b7-b6 instead, and I believe that the pawn on a6 will be misplaced.} 
8. Qb3 {This is important prophylaxis. Sadly, White cannot play Qc4-c2 as he would in the mainline, as then Black would equalize with b7-b5. We need to keep the d5-square under control so that Black will be unable to play Nf6-d5 to clog the long diagonal. Next up, we will play a2-a4 to prevent b7-b5 forever, and if allowed, a4-a5.   One day, this will force Black to play b7-b5 and allow a5xb6 at a moment when Black will be missing his a7-pawn, and be left with a sorry structure. I think Black should play either Ra8-a7 or Qc8-c7, making sure to immediately be ready to meet a2-a4 with b7-b6 before a4-a5 can come. Still, I don't believe this will guarantee equality for the second player.} 
8. Qc7 {This is a typical move for the line, hoping to play b7-b5 next and being ready to meet any annoying discovery on the long diagonal with Bc8-b7. But, the queen can be awkward here as well.8...b5?9.Ne5!White wins material, thanks in no small part to the foresight of putting the queen on b3 rather than any other square. Black cannot clog the long diagonal.} 
9. a4 {We will see this move against a lot of Black's responses. White's contention here is that the weakness of the c4-square and the b6-pawn makes Black's position a bit uncomfortable, and the queen on c7 will eventually lose a tempo to Bc1-f4.} 
9. b6
10. Na3
10. Bb7
11. Nc4 {Black did get his bishop to the long diagonal, but at a cost. He will lose time to Bc1-f4 next, and the b6-pawn is a long-term liability since it will be very hard to play Ra8-b8 and the a-pawn cannot move backward. White looks a bit better here, and it says a lot that the machine claims that Black's best move is Bf8-d6, voluntarily ceding the bishop pair.   In general, I think this position very clearly highlights the drawback of playing a7-a6 and then b7-b6. If Black's pawn were back on a7 here, he would surely be fine without a queenside weakness to babysit. To illustrate this point, we'll see the 11... Be7 12. Bf4 line.} 
11. Bd6 {11...Be712.Bf4is covered here.} 
12. O-O
12. O-O
13. e4 {I can't really believe Black will equalize here. White can grab a bishop pair whenever he wants it, and can someday hope to play Bc1-d2, Qb3-a3, and b2-b4. We will see David Navara put on a clinic from a similar position in the annotated games section.} 
