8. h5 {While this move was not entirely unknown before my course came out, I still think of it as my brainchild and I suspect I had something to do with it gaining popularity. Black's point is simple. While we spend a bunch of time recapturing the lost pawn and dragging our knights away from the kingside, he launches a direct counterattack,} 
9. Naxc4 {I am not a believer in pushing h2-h4 too often. It seldom helps Black much in the Dragon as g2-g4 still comes, and here I would fear a well timed g7-g5. White should be looking for direct play in the center.} 
9. Nxc4
10. Nxc4
10. h4 {It would blow my mind to see Black play anything else.} 
11. Ne5
11. hxg3
12. hxg3 {We are still following my course.} 
12. Qd4 {The best move, and not an easy one. Black provokes White's queen to c3 before tucking back to d6.12...Qd6?13.d4!Just like that, Black is in huge trouble. The queen is much better on c2 than on c3. This can be most clearly seen in this line.} 
13. Qc3
13. Rd8
14. Qxd4
14. Rxd4
15. d3 {White should be a bit better here thanks to his central pawns. In general, I think Black's best hope of fighting for equality is to keep the queens on the board. It is more consistent with the h7-h5-h4 attacking plan, and it makes it harder for White to gain further space with a move like f2-f4.   As is, f2-f4 will come very easily, Bc1-e3 is a great square, and Black will struggle to develop his kingside. Eventually, we may want to look for b2-b4-b5 once Black's rook has been kicked off d4.} 
