1. c4
1. Nf6 {•1...g6If Black wants a setup with c6 and d5, aiming to play a solid version of the Fianchetto Grunfeld, This is probably a better move order for him.2.g3Both now and on move 3, Black could consider e7-e5 or c7-c5, which will be covered in the second part.2...c63.Bg2d54.Nf3Bg75.O-ONf66.b3In this exact position with d2-d4 and O-O included, I believe Black equalizes easily with either Bc8-f5 or simply taking on c4 and pushing c6-c5. Here, against both of these plans, we can take full advantage of our pawn being on d2 rather than d4, and I believe this gives us a much greater chance of fighting for an advantage than we would have had in a traditional Fianchetto Grunfeld with a 1. d4 move order.•1...g62.g3c63.Bg2d54.Nf3Bg75.O-Oe56.d3This position is generally thought of as harmless for Black without the moves c2-c4 and c7-c6 included, but with them on the board, I think we have a chance to put him under pressure.} 
2. g3
2. g6
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3 {Black is not able to play a c6+d5 setup, nor is he able to play a d5 setup without c6. He is really forced into a King's Indian, and I believe I have found a way to put his position under some pressure. I don't have the highest opinion of the King's Indian, but one of its biggest appeals is that Black absolutely does not care about White's move order in the slightest, and unless he is facing 1. e4, he can basically go 1... Nf6, 2... g6, 3... Bg7, and 4... O-O against more or less any legal move.   This is in stark contrast to Black's other g6 defense against d4, the Grunfeld, which is certainly a better opening but also more susceptible to move order tricks. Case in point, we will not have to really deal with it here.   That said, we also will be lacking some of the most ambitious options that White normally would choose, and we have to content ourselves with looking for a modest edge.} 
4. O-O
5. d4 {Now, for the most part, I have aimed to keep this repertoire as unique as possible, and to avoid transposing to any 1. d4 lines if I can help it. But, here, I am very convinced that the only way to fight for an edge is to push d2-d4, and we will transpose into a Fianchetto King's Indian where Black was unable to make the best use of his more solid options with c6 and d5 earlier on.} 
