[Black "g6/Bg7 Setups: 1...g6 2.g3 c6 with 5...Nf6 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. g6 {This move might look like it is just destined to transpose back into the normal mainline King's Indian setups, but in fact it is quite a clever move order if Black wants to play with c7-c6 and d7-d5.} 
2. g3 {Now,2...e5and2...c5transpose to what will be covered in future courses. If Black does not choose one of these options, I would be pretty surprised to see him do anything other than Bf8-g7 and Ng8-f6 in the next couple of moves.} 
2. c6 {Black can also play2...Bg73.Bg2and3...c6to reach the same positions.3...Nf64.Nc3transposes to the main line.4.Nf3d55.O-ONf66.b3!transposes to the 2... c6 move order.} 
3. Bg2
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. O-O {Now, Black has a choice to make. He can either play Ng8-f6, keeping the game in line with a more normal looking c6+d5 Fianchetto Grunfeld, or he can push e7-e5, aiming to take it into a position that more resembles a Reti.} 
5. Nf6 {This has to be considered the main move.} 
6. b3 {Now, I believe White should be slightly better if he can play Bc1-b2. His b2-bishop will then be no worse than its counterpart on g7, while a strong case can be made that the c8-bishop will be worse than its counterpart on g2. But, thanks to Black's clever move order, he does have an additional option to provoke a conflict in the center.} 
6. O-O {This obvious looking move is actually quite cooperative. Now, once White gets his bishop to b2, Black will not be able to try to complicate matters any more.} 
7. Bb2 {Now, according to my database, Black has tried 21 (!) different moves here. It's not wildly surprising, as the position is very non-forcing in its nature. In general, whenever you come across a position like that, it becomes pretty futile to go deep into any concrete variations, and it becomes much more important to understand the key themes and check some sample lines.   In general, I think White's best plan is to set up with d2-d4, Nb1-c3, Ra1-c1, e2-e3, Qd1-e2, and Rf1-d1. Then, he can eventually look for Nf3-e5. I don't see a great way for Black to set up his pieces that avoids this, but I did check a couple of moves that looked reasonable to me.7.d4This move would take us back to 1. d4 territory. It gives Black a direct option that he should definitely make good use of.7...dxc4!8.bxc4c5=Because White pushed d2-d4 before playing Bc1-b2 (if he reached the present position, he most likely pushed d2-d4 on the first move of the game), White is unable to play d4-d5 here. As a result, Black can take on d4, messing up the structure, and I think he should be fine.} 
7. Re8 {This move was once played against me by Jorge Cori. It's not a terrible move by any stretch, but I don't really believe it will equalize either. It's only point is to prepare for e7-e5 to come later, and since d2-d4 was part of our plan anyway, it feels like we can do our thing and stop Black's main idea at the same time.} 
8. d4 {Of course. But now we see a point in playing Rf8-e8 instead of Nb8-d7. By leaving the knight at home for the moment, Black can hope to bring the bishop to f5 or g4 before playing Nb8-d7.} 
8. Bf5 {The bishop does make sense here now, and I think Black would probably be fine if he had not burned a tempo on Rf8-e8, which looks pretty useless at the present moment.} 
9. Nc3
9. Nbd7 {Black's position looks harmonious enough, but I think he is still a bit worse. The bishop on f5 will be in danger of being trapped if Black ever plays e7-e6, which makes it hard to him to properly support the center.} 
10. Rc1 {White has the same plan of e2-e3, Qd1-e2, and Rf1-d1 with Nf3-e5 to follow. It's thin, but not nothing and the computers consistently give the first player a little pull. The tempo burned on Rf8-e8 means that Black's direct attempt to equalize will not work.} 
10. dxc4
11. bxc4
11. Nb6 {Black should avoid this move, but he is a little worse all the same.} 
12. c5
12. Nc4 {If White's bishop were forced back to c1 here, Black would be in reasonable shape.} 
13. Ba1 {Black is in huge trouble and the knight on c4 will be a liability. e2-e4 could come next.} 
