[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Setups with g6/Bg7, Black plays ...d5"]
[Black "g6/Bg7 Setups: 1...g6 2.g3 c6 with 5...Nf6 #13"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. g6 {This move might look like it is just destined to transpose back into the normal mainline King's Indian setups, but in fact it is quite a clever move order if Black wants to play with c7-c6 and d7-d5.} 
2. g3 {Now,2...e5and2...c5transpose to what will be covered in future courses. If Black does not choose one of these options, I would be pretty surprised to see him do anything other than Bf8-g7 and Ng8-f6 in the next couple of moves.} 
2. c6 {Black can also play2...Bg73.Bg2and3...c6to reach the same positions.3...Nf64.Nc3transposes to the main line.4.Nf3d55.O-ONf66.b3!transposes to the 2... c6 move order.} 
3. Bg2
3. d5
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. O-O {Now, Black has a choice to make. He can either play Ng8-f6, keeping the game in line with a more normal looking c6+d5 Fianchetto Grunfeld, or he can push e7-e5, aiming to take it into a position that more resembles a Reti.} 
5. Nf6 {This has to be considered the main move.} 
6. b3 {Now, I believe White should be slightly better if he can play Bc1-b2. His b2-bishop will then be no worse than its counterpart on g7, while a strong case can be made that the c8-bishop will be worse than its counterpart on g2. But, thanks to Black's clever move order, he does have an additional option to provoke a conflict in the center.} 
6. Ne4 {I think this is far and away Black's best move. He hits us on the long diagonal and forces us to advance d2-d4 before getting our bishop to b2, but this does come at a cost.} 
7. d4
7. dxc4
8. bxc4
8. c5 {This position would be totally normal, and totally fine for Black if he had castled instead of playing Nf6-e4. As is, he is overextended, underdeveloped, and not ready for the center to open like this.} 
9. Qc2
9. Nd6 {9...Bf5g4!Black loses material, and the game.} 
10. Bb2 {Black is way too underdeveloped to allow the center to open like this. White easily brings more pieces into play and the machine claims he is already winning.} 
