9. Be6
10. Qc2
10. f5 {This has been Black's most common move, and by that, I mean played four times.10...Nd611.Nd2White is ready for e2-e4 to come next. He should be a bit better.} 
11. e3 {I don't believe in a Stonewall for Black with the bishop on g7. One of the biggest prides of his position in a proper Stonewall is the great bishop on d6 that is not so easy for White to challenge. Black will totally lack the kind of kingside counterplay he is looking for, and White should be better with the normal knight regrouping of Nh4-f3 and Nb1-c3-e2.} 
