8. e4 {I like starting with e2-e4. This disallows some trickery with Nd7-b6.8.O-Oexd49.Nxd4Nb6This line is not amazing for Black, but I see no reason to allow it and burden our memory even further.} 
8. c6 {Once upon a time, the plan involving leaving the pawn on e5 and playing some kind of Qd8-b6 had some merit to it. In modern times, the machines just laugh. Black should stick to taking on d4 and putting the knight on c5.} 
9. O-O
9. a6 {As usual, combining a6 and e5 doesn't make much sense to me. It's only major appeal is that it does a good job of making us not want to play Rf1-e1 here, which is by far our most consistent move. This is the only place that you have to remember to play something different.} 
10. Be3 {White gets the bishop to its best square, pointing out that a7-a6 is completely unhelpful in making counterplay against the e4-pawn.} 
10. b5 {This almost looks like it makes sense, but...10...Qc7This could try to prepare for b7-b5, but we have a very natural move that prevents it,11.Rc1.} 
11. c5 {Black is in big trouble since he cannot take on d4 thanks to the hanging c6-pawn.For example,11...dxc512.dxe5Ne813.Bxc5+-, or11...b412.Na4Nxe413.cxd6Nxd614.Nxe5Nxe515.dxe5Nc416.Bc5±} 
