y playing a7-a5, making sure to meet b2-b3 with a5-a4.   2. If he does not play a7-a5, we will play b2-b3. Then, should a7-a5 come, we should spend a move on Ra1-b1 before playing Bc1-b2, making sure that we can meet a5-a4 with b2-b4 without a4-a3 coming in response.   3. If Black plays a7-a5 before we can play b2-b3, then we will play Nd4-b5, taking advantage of the weakened b5-square. The bishop will then be fantastic on f4, and can come back to e3 if it is ever kicked by Nf6-h5.   4. If Black ever puts his d7-knight on e5, we usually can aim for maximum punishment and put the bishop on e3. The biggest drawback of the bishop going to e3 is that Black can attack the e4-pawn with some combination of Nd7-c5 and Rf8-e8, and this is not a thing anymore once the knight goes to e5.} 
8. e4 {I like starting with e2-e4. This disallows some trickery with Nd7-b6.8.O-Oexd49.Nxd4Nb6This line is not amazing for Black, but I see no reason to allow it and burden our memory even further.} 
8. c6 {Once upon a time, the plan involving leaving the pawn on e5 and playing some kind of Qd8-b6 had some merit to it. In modern times, the machines just laugh. Black should stick to taking on d4 and putting the knight on c5.} 
9. O-O
9. exd4
10. Nxd4
10. Nc5
11. Re1 {As always, we continue with Re1.} 
11. a5
12. Bf4 {And when a5 comes, we put our bishop on f4. White has an easy position with Qd2 and Rad1 coming next.} 
*
