1. c4 {•1.d4Nf62.c4e63.Nf3d54.g3This is the starting position of the mainline Catalan from a 1. d4 move order. When considering Black's 3 main strategies, here he has some additional options. First of all, taking on c4 and trying to hold onto it is a real plan since Qd1-a4+ in response is a much worse version when White has already committed to d2-d4, and also Black has the option to give a check on b4.4...Bb4+5.Nbd2dxc4White will not get this pawn back.•1.d4Nf62.c4e63.Nf3d54.g3dxc45.Qa4+This would be the analogous move to our repertoire, taking the pawn on c4 back directly and not allowing Black to attempt to hold onto it. But, the pawn on d4 is now a detriment.5...Nbd76.Qxc4a6!White is unable to prevent b7-b5, and Black's bishop will get to b7. Black should be totally fine.•1.d4Nf62.c4e63.Nf3d54.g3dxc45.Bg2This is White's main move. Now, Black has several interesting options aiming to hang onto the c4-pawn, all of which require very precise treatment.5...c6,5...b5,5...a6,5...Bb4+,5...Nc6,5...Bd7•1.d4Nf62.c4e63.Nf3d54.g3Bb4+5.Bd2Be7Strategy 3 is on full display. Black is ready for ...O-O, ...c6, ...b6, and ...Bb7.6.Bg2O-O7.O-Oc68.Qc2Nbd7In this structure, the way White would want to make his g2-bishop better than the c8-bishop would be to push e2-e4. Because Black was able to provoke White's bishop to d2 thanks to Bf8-b4 being a check, White is not able to play Nbd2 and e2-e4 so easily.} 
1. e6 {By playing e6 on the first move, Black is advertising that he wishes to go into some kind of Queen's Gambit Declined. As usual, we play g3 on the second move.} 
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {The combination of the pawn on c4 and the bishop on g2 makes the position look a lot like a Catalan. Indeed, at many junctures, White could certainly push d2-d4 and reach a direct transposition, using the move order to avoid some of Black's best lines. But, in our case, we are mostly trying to keep this repertoire as close to the English as possible and transposing to 1. d4 lines as rarely as we can.   The ambition of White's setup when playing against any kind of line featuring d7-d5 is very simple. He is trying to claim that the bishop on g2 will be better than the bishop on c8, which is currently shut in by Black's own e6-pawn.   From Black's point of view, much like he faces in a mainline Catalan from a 1. d4 move order, he has to first choose his general strategy, and then choose how to implement it. Broadly speaking, I believe there are 5 ways Black can try to fight for equality, of which 3 are relevant in this section. He can:   1. Take the c4 pawn and try to hold onto it. He will not easily solve the problem of his c8-bishop being a lousy piece, but an extra pawn counts for something. This proves to be impossible given our move order when Black plays 1... e6, and will only become relevant in the final section featuring playing with c7-c6 instead.   2. Take on c4, not hold onto it, but use the time that White spends taking it back to get his c8-bishop to the long diagonal, effectively neutralizing our main advantage in this line. This is seen in the mainline Catalan, and is seen here as well, but the absence of d2-d4 makes the positions very different for both sides.   3. Maintain the pawn on d5 and try to argue that when he keeps the center this solid, White's light-squared bishop may not be better than Black's after all. This is in theory possible here, but not great, and I think this strategy works better for Black when facing a 1.d4 order and playing into a mainline Catalan.   4. Push d5-d4 and completely change the character of the game to make it a reversed Benoni rather than a Catalan. This possibility aims at taking advantage of our move order and choice not to place a pawn on d4 (say, on the first move of the game) before Black can.   5. Black can get the bishop outside of the pawn chain by means of Bc8-f5 or Bc8-g4 before pushing e7-e6, trying to claim that this bishop will be no worse than its counterpart on g2. Obviously, Black's very first move in this section rules out this strategy for now, but it will become relevant in the final part concerning c6 and d5 setups.   Once Black has chosen one of these strategies, he then has to choose how to implement it, and this is where specific details and concrete moves come into play.} 
3. Nf6 {3...dxc4Black can take on c4 directly as well, but I don't think it changes much.4.Qa4+White takes the pawn back directly.} 
4. Nf3
4. dxc4 {This is Black's last reasonable opportunity to try to capture on c4.4...Be75.O-OO-O6.b3We aim to play into a Closed Catalan structure where Black was unable to provoke our bishop to the inferior d2-square. Black is very solid here, but I think I was able to put his position under some pressure.} 
5. Qa4+ {White takes back the pawn on c4 without allowing Black to attempt to defend it. The rest of the opening will revolve around Black attempting to get his c8-bishop to the long diagonal, and our attempt to stop him.} 
