3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. In the present chapter, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. g6 {Aleksandr Rakhmanov once played this setup against me. I really don't see much point to it, and it feels like Black cannot make up his mind as to whether he wants to play a Grunfeld or a Catalan.} 
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. d4 {I like taking the whole center and transposing back into a 1. d4 opening, albeit a strange one for Black. Basically here, I think he will fail to execute any of his three main strategies for dealing with the Catalan. If he takes on c4, he surely will not hold onto it, and the lost time on e7-e6 and g7-g6 means he will not be able to contest the long diagonal either.} 
5. Nf6
6. O-O
6. O-O
7. Nc3 {We have transposed into something somewhat resembling a Fianchetto Grunfeld where the move e7-e6 is totally out of place, and White should have a very nice position with b2-b3 and Bc1-b2 next. Note that Black can never really hope to take on c4.} 
7. dxc4
8. Qa4 {Why has Black played e7-e6, rather than c7-c6? He does not get to play b5. White takes back on c4 next and has a huge position already.} 
