2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. In the present chapter, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. c6 {Trying to bolster the center in the style of the Semi-Slav strikes me as less than ideal.} 
4. Nf3
4. Nf6 {4...dxc4will transpose to the 2... c6 section.} 
5. b3 {White goes ahead and builds his main setup, preventing any hope of Black taking on d4. I generally don't think that c7-c6 mixes well with the rest of Black's play in this line.} 
5. Be7
6. Bb2
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Nbd7 {Now, there is nothing wrong with playing d2-d4, now or on the next move, aiming to reach a mainline Catalan where Black has played a less than critical response. But I actually like taking advantage of the d-pawn staying home.} 
8. d3 {White has a very simple plan of Qd1-c2, Nb1-d2, and e2-e4 to take space in the center. I don't see anything great for Black to try, and he looks a bit worse. For example, I'd think the most thematic move is b7-b6, continuing development in the style of the Closed Catalan.} 
8. b6 {8...b59.Nbd2Much like we see in the main line, White is ready for e2-e4 next and Black's position looks structurally dubious. His bishop on c8 will have a real problem finding any activity. And remember, always meet b5xc4 with d3xc4.} 
9. e4 {Already, Black is facing unpleasant pressure. He cannot take on e4.} 
9. Bb7 {This feels most thematic.9...dxe4?10.dxe4Nxe411.Nd4+-Black is collapsing.} 
10. cxd5
10. cxd5
11. e5 {The pawn on d3 might look dumb, but I'm actually quite happy to have not allowed Nf6-e4.} 
11. Ne8
12. Nc3 {Black's position looks very suspicious to me. I like the extra space, and White can even consider launching a direct attack with Nf3-e1 and f2-f4.} 
