2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. In the present chapter, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. d4 {One of the best ways for Black to attempt to punish us for playing the English is to immediately point out that we might regret not having a pawn on d4. Indeed, this would be a fourth strategy for how to fight for equality in the Catalan that does not exist within a 1. d4 move order.   Still, this idea highlights one of the biggest reasons that I chose to do an English repertoire and not a Reti. By starting with c2-c4 on move 1, we make it impossible for Black to push d7-d5-d4 without first playing c7-c6 or e7-e6, as he has done here. Once a Benoni structure is reached, it should be pretty clear that the pawn on e6 would rather be on e5.} 
