9. Nd7 {This move is Jorden van Foreest's recommendation for Black in his recently released  Tarrasch repertoire. It's not a bad move, but I have a hard time believing in a knight's tour against the reversed Benoni when the pawn has to remain on e6 rather than e5.} 
10. Na3 {One problem with playing something a little shaky that probably sort of holds together with precise play is that your opponent tends to have endless options. Jorden did not consider this natural move, and instead focused his energies on dealing with10.Re1and10.Qe2,both of which make a lot of sense as well. But I like this move a lot. In general, the plan of bringing the knight back to c2 in against the knight's tour will guarantee the b2-b4 advance, and our opponent's best plan should be to bring his knight to c5 and bishop to f5 to crash through on d3 before this can happen. Black is a long way from executing this plan, so as such, I think we can aim for a  quick b2-b4.} 
10. Be7 {This feels the most thematic to me, but I think we can proceed along in the same manner as against ...Bc5.} 
