[Black "e6/d5 Setups: 3...d4 4.Nf3 Nf6 #17"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. In the present chapter, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. d4 {One of the best ways for Black to attempt to punish us for playing the English is to immediately point out that we might regret not having a pawn on d4. Indeed, this would be a fourth strategy for how to fight for equality in the Catalan that does not exist within a 1. d4 move order.   Still, this idea highlights one of the biggest reasons that I chose to do an English repertoire and not a Reti. By starting with c2-c4 on move 1, we make it impossible for Black to push d7-d5-d4 without first playing c7-c6 or e7-e6, as he has done here. Once a Benoni structure is reached, it should be pretty clear that the pawn on e6 would rather be on e5.} 
4. Nf3
4. Nf6
5. O-O {Now, Black's most common and most principled move is c7-c5. This will take the game into a Benoni structure where White is effectively up 2 tempi because 1. He is White and got the first move and 2. Black has played e7-e6 rather than e7-e5. However, this does not necessarily guarantee an advantage. Being 2 tempi up on a bad position is an improvement, but how much does it change the evaluation? I think White is on the more comfortable side of equality and can force Black to find some good moves.} 
5. c5
6. e3
6. Nc6
7. exd4
7. cxd4
8. d3 {Now, it is a well-known rule that when playing against the Benoni, you want to avoid piece exchanges. So, Black should not be thrilled about allowing Bc1-g5. But, I don't think he has much of a choice.} 
8. Bd6
9. Bg5
9. h6
10. Bxf6 {Intending Nbd2-Ne4 next.} 
10. Qxf6
11. Nbd2
11. Qd8 {This is another way for Black to avoid the exchange of minor pieces, but I think he will regret not bringing the queen back to e7.} 
12. Rc1 {Simple and strong. White takes advantage of Black's queen going all the way back home and points out that he is ready for c4-c5 to come next.} 
12. O-O
13. c5
13. Be7 {This is probably Black's best, trying to keep the knight off of c4. After13...Bc714.Nc4!White looks pleasantly better, and can play Qd1-e2 next, aiming to play Nf3-e5 to start trading more pieces. It's nice that this move is possible as c5 is not hanging!} 
14. Qa4 {White continues to grow his lead in development. Black is forced to respect the idea of b2-b4 coming next.} 
14. Bd7
15. Nxd4 {This is an important move to remember since it looks a bit scary, but White wins a reasonably clean pawn. Black lacks a good discovery.} 
15. Nxd4
16. Qxd4
16. Bc6
17. Qc4
17. b5
18. Qb3 {This is a very important and very good square for White's queen. Following an exchange on g2, Black will not be able to give a check on d5 to quickly get a rook to d8 and capture d3. As far as I can see, White is a healthy pawn up.} 
