[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2 {Previously, we have seen Black attempt to execute strategy 2 by taking on c4, and hoping to make use of the time White spends recapturing the pawn to contest the long diagonal. In the present chapter, we will look at what happens if Black aims to maintain his pawn on d5 and argue that the bishop on g2 is no better than its counterpart on c8.} 
3. Nf6
4. Nf3
4. Be7 {4...a6?!I've seen this move before, but it doesn't make much sense to me. I guess the point is to hope to take on c4 next when White cannot simply grab the pawn back with a check on a4, but b2-b3 was part of our plan anyway.5.b3±a7-a6 feels really out of place. White gets the setup he wants.4...d4This is weird timing for Black, but it should not have any independent value.5.O-OBlack will have to play either c7-c5, transposing to the 3... c4 line, or Bf8-e7, transposing to the mainline.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O {Now, a very common move here is d2-d4, using the English move order to force Black into a mainline Catalan where he has not been able to make use of his additional options, such as taking on c4 early or giving Bb4+ and Be7 back. But, this opens up a whole new can of worms, and I prefer to keep the game firmly in English territory.5...c56.b3transposes after both6...Nc6and6...O-O.} 
6. b3 {Throughout this entire repertoire, I had the interesting experience of going through Mihail Marin's old recommendations, deciding which spots best stood the test of time, and which spots I wanted to take a different direction. Ultimately here, I decided to play the same 6. b3 that he had popularized in his books, but after this, I want to play very different plans against most of Black's moves than what he originally recommended.} 
6. b6 {Bringing the bishop to b7 makes a lot of sense. Black points out that he can meet cxd5 with Nxd5, and then Bb7 comes and he should be more or less fine. But, I think now is a good time to transpose into a more normal Catalan, when Black is extremely restricted and unable to play his best option.} 
7. d4 {I like this move a lot. We managed to get into a mainline Catalan with b3, a line that I have often played through a 1. d4 move order, at a moment when Black cannot play his best plan of d5xc4 followed by c7-c5.} 
7. Bb7 {Now, White should be very careful to play the right move order.7...dxc4?8.Ne5Black can already resign.} 
8. Nc3 {By pressuring the d5-square, we are once again avoiding ...dxc4 followed by ...c5.} 
8. dxc4
9. bxc4
9. Ne4 {This should be preferred.} 
10. Nxe4
10. Bxe4
11. Qb3 {With Rf1-d1 to follow next, I can't really believe Black will equalize. He will not be able to comfortably push c7-c5 without allowing d4-d5 in response.} 
