4. Nf3
4. Be7 {4...a6?!I've seen this move before, but it doesn't make much sense to me. I guess the point is to hope to take on c4 next when White cannot simply grab the pawn back with a check on a4, but b2-b3 was part of our plan anyway.5.b3±a7-a6 feels really out of place. White gets the setup he wants.4...d4This is weird timing for Black, but it should not have any independent value.5.O-OBlack will have to play either c7-c5, transposing to the 3... c4 line, or Bf8-e7, transposing to the mainline.} 
5. O-O
5. O-O {Now, a very common move here is d2-d4, using the English move order to force Black into a mainline Catalan where he has not been able to make use of his additional options, such as taking on c4 early or giving Bb4+ and Be7 back. But, this opens up a whole new can of worms, and I prefer to keep the game firmly in English territory.5...c56.b3transposes after both6...Nc6and6...O-O.} 
6. b3 {Throughout this entire repertoire, I had the interesting experience of going through Mihail Marin's old recommendations, deciding which spots best stood the test of time, and which spots I wanted to take a different direction. Ultimately here, I decided to play the same 6. b3 that he had popularized in his books, but after this, I want to play very different plans against most of Black's moves than what he originally recommended.} 
6. d4 {This seems like a very reasonable time for Black to try to transition the position into some kind of Benoni, arguing that b2-b3 is not the most useful move for White in this structure. I think it is probably his best move, and maybe one of his best lines on the whole in this entire repertoire. He surely should be fine objectively, but I did some digging on a new-ish idea that I think contains some venom.} 
7. e3
7. c5 {Until recently, White had taken on d4 in nearly every game to reach this position. He should have a fantastic reversed Benoni, but it is a Benoni all the same. He certainly is not worse and has reasonable chances to play a complicated game, and I even lost on the black side of this position once to Hari (Pentala Harikrishna, Chessable Note) back when I was 2650. But, for this repertoire, I prefer something a little fresher.} 
8. Ne5 {I like this move a lot, highlighting that Black is further behind in development than he would like to be. Normally in a Benoni, you should not be able to occupy this square so easily. White's goal is to bolster his knight with f2-f4 if needed, and he is always happy to trade a pair of pieces.} 
8. Nbd7 {This feels very human to me.} 
9. exd4
9. cxd4
10. Nxd7 {Anyone who has studied my d4 repertoire should know that the guy playing the Benoni (White in this case) is very happy to exchange a pair of minor pieces.} 
10. Nxd7 {10...Qxd711.d3Black's coordination is all wrong and White should be a bit better. He will bring his knight to e4, and then when a2-a3 and Bc1-d2 come, he will be able to start pushing on the queenside.10...Bxd7?11.Bxb7White wins a pawn.} 
11. d3 {My computer claims this position is absolutely equal. In a higher chess sense, I think it is right. But in human play, I would definitely prefer White here. Black's pieces are completely not set up to contain the Benoni advances on the queenside, and they are also not set up to pressure the d3-pawn or push e6-e5-e4.   White has a very simple plan. He will go Bc1-a3, trade dark-squared bishops, then Nb1-d2, Qd1-e2, a2-a3 and start pushing on the queenside. In practice, it should be easier to handle from the White side.} 
