8. Qc7 {The machine is pretty agnostic here, not seeing much difference in evaluation between Qd8-c7 and some knight to d7 instead. But, I am very confident that this is Black's best move.} 
9. f4 {White bolsters the knight. This is the line where it becomes clear why it is important to wait on capturing d4. It's nice that we never have to worry about the option going away since d4xe3 always leaves Black with an awful position.} 
9. Nfd7 {This is a very natural move. I think we now have to take on d4 because if we were to retreat the knight as we do in the mainline, Black will follow up with Nb8-c6 and be ready to recapture on d4 with the knight instead,} 
10. exd4 {10.Nd3?!Nc6I don't trust this so much for White. When we take on d4, Black may take back with a piece.} 
10. cxd4
11. Nd3
11. Nc6
12. Ba3 {Again, we see this same plan. White wants to trade off more minor pieces and can hope to expand on the queenside later.} 
12. Qd8
13. Bxe7
13. Qxe7 {Now, the machine reads equal more or less no matter what anyone does, but the position obviously has a lot of life in it. I like being consistent in trying to trade more pieces.} 
14. Qc1 {White is ready for Qc1-a3 next. I think the endgame should be very nice for him, and the computer is starting to claim that Black needs to find weird moves to not be worse. In practice, I would definitely prefer White here.} 
