3. dxc4 {This move order doesn't help Black much, and may even reduce his options to some degree. I'd expect him to mainly play3...Nf6and only take on c4 next once White's knight has committed to f3, but transpositions are reasonably likely.} 
4. Qa4+ {As mentioned in the introduction, I want to immediately grab the pawn back on c4 without allowing Black the option of trying to hang onto it. As we will see, this becomes much more feasible in the present position than it would be in a 1. d4 line.} 
4. c6 {4...Nd75.Qxc4Now, Black will need to play Ng8-f6 sooner or later, transposing to the next chapter.5...c55...a66.Qc2!Black has nothing better than Ng8-f6 here, transposing to the next chapter.6.Nf3a67.Qc2!For some foreshadowing, in the next chapter, we will also see White meeting a7-a6 with Qc4-c2.7...Ngf68.Nc3transposes to the next chapter.} 
5. Qxc4
