[Black "e6/d5 Setups: 3...Nf6 4.Nf3 Be7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2
3. Nf6
4. Nf3 {Now, this is Black's last moment to reasonably hope to capture on c4.} 
4. Be7 {With this move, Black is almost certainly attempting to castle next and not bother taking on c4- this position will be covered in the next chapter. But it is also important to note that he has really lost his option at this point.} 
5. O-O
5. dxc4 {Now, checking on a4 like we often see is certainly reasonable, but I really like aiming for maximum punishment.5...O-O!transposes to the next chapter.} 
6. Na3 {White can take back on c4 in a more active manner. The way Black would normally punish this move would be to take on a3, but now this means the loss of a tempo.} 
6. Bxa3 {6...O-O7.Nxc4⩲White has an excellent version of the Catalan. Normally, when Black takes on c4 and lets White recapture, he is hoping that White will have to take back with the queen, and that she will then lose more time. By taking with the knight, White has a very pleasant position and can look to follow up with d2-d4 next.} 
7. bxa3 {White will easily take back the lost pawn with Qd1-c2, and then his active bishops promise him a nice edge. Black is lacking the necessary resources to equalize when he is playing the position with a tempo less.} 
7. b5 {This would be the equalizing move if White had not yet castled. But, an extra tempo is enormous in such a sharp position.} 
8. a4
8. a6
9. Ne5
9. Nd5
10. d3 {White is blasting open the position. Black is in massive trouble no matter how he plays, but I like one line in particular for its illustrative nature.} 
10. Qd6 {Now, anything wins, but the most thematic is Nxc4!10...c311.e4Nb612.Ba3!Black will not castle and soon will face a vicious attack. Qd1-h5 is coming next.} 
11. Nxc4
11. bxc4
12. dxc4 {Since White has already castled, thanks to the tempo lost on Bf8-e7-xa3, Black does not have a check on b4. He may as well resign.} 
