16. Be1 {I like this move, aimed as prophylaxis against Black ever-pushing c5-c4.  Additionally, by overprotecting d3, White can hope for e2-e3 to come next.} 
16. Nd6
17. e3 {Next up is a2-a3 and we will be ready for b2-b4 sooner or later. Since Black brought his knight to d6 rather than d5, we won't need to put a rook on b1 to push b4 through. The machine still claims Black is more or less fine here, but it's another typical position for this line - all of Black's pieces are on their best squares, he cannot improve his position any further, and he has to sit, wait, and just hope that he is solid enough to stop b2-b4 forever. It's not easy to play chess like this, and I would definitely prefer White here.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "5) Setups with e6/d5,  ...dxc4 w/o ...Nbd7"]
[Black "e6/d5 Setups: 3...Nf6 4.Nf3 dxc4 with 5...c6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2
3. Nf6
4. Nf3 {Now, this is Black's last moment to reasonably hope to capture on c4.} 
4. dxc4
5. Qa4+ {White takes back the pawn on c4 without allowing Black to attempt to defend it. Now, Black has a few options of how to get his pieces out.5.Na3?!This would be the move aiming for maximum punishment, hoping to take back with the knight on c4. It was also the recommendation of Mihail Marin in his original work for Quality Chess once upon a time, which has long been held up as the gold standard for the Fianchetto English. But, I don't think it stood the test of time too well. Black can take on a3 in one move, and he should be fine.5...Bxa36.bxa3b5!I don't think Black has much to complain about. He is ready for Bc8-b7 and can always plug the long diagonal with Nf6-d5 if needed. The machine even offers him some edge- he is up a pawn after all. White is not fast enough to generate a serious initiative.} 
5. c6 {This move has seen some play too, and it has its merits. Unlike what we will see next chapter with Nb8-d7, Black doesn't leave anything up to chance and will clearly accomplish b7-b5 next, which speaks heavily in his favor. That said, he still will not fix his light squared bishop without pushing c6-c5 later, which will cost him a valuable tempo.} 
6. Qxc4
6. Be7 {While this is where the bishop would like to go, it allows White an additional option that he could make use of.} 
7. d4
7. b5 {Now, there is surely nothing wrong with Qc4-b3, which should promptly transpose to the chapter's mainline, but I quite like an additional option.} 
8. Qd3 {This strikes me as the best square for the queen. She is still harassing the b5-pawn and feels a little less awkward than she does on b3.} 
