17. Qf6
18. Rc7 {White's pieces are springing to life. It is a very bad sign for Black that the machine wants him to play Bb7-c8.} 
18. Rab8 {This feels like the human move to me. White should be precise.} 
19. h4 {The threat of Bf4-g5 is rather obvious. I struggle to imagine a human being not pushing h7-h6 in response.} 
19. h6
20. Qe3 {Now we follow a forced line. The threat of Bf4-e5 forces Be7-d8.} 
20. Bd8
21. Rd7
21. Bc6
22. Bxb8
22. Bxd7
23. Bd6
23. Qxb2 {This move would work without h2-h4 and h7-h6 included, but here it falls on its face.} 
24. Bxf8
24. Kxf8
25. Bxd5 {An important move, without which Black would surely be fine with the two pawns for the exchange. As is, he collapses on the d-file.} 
25. exd5
26. Rxd5
26. Qb1+ {Now, we see the deep tactical point behind the inclusion of h2-h4 and h7-h6.} 
27. Kh2 {It's nice to have this square available and not have to walk right into Bd7-c6. Black can resign.} 
