8. Nbd7 {In general, in all of the lines where Black is trying to take on c4 and get b5 in, he usually needs to leave the bishop on f8 for awhile and develop his queenside first.8...a69.Ne5Nbd710.d4transpose to the mainline.} 
9. d4
9. a6 {Now, Black is ready for c6-c5 to come next. If he is allowed to play it, he will surely equalize right away, and he will be happy to have not burned any time with his f8-bishop, as it can take back in one move without having to stop on e7 in between. If we want to keep him under pressure, we are forced into action right away.} 
10. Ne5 {The only testing move. White clears his knight off of the long diagonal, opening up the bishop on g2 to pin the c6-pawn. If White could stabilize this position and not allow Black to play c6-c5 on a permanent basis with no changes to the structure, he should be more or less winning. But, this move does allow Black to double the pawns in the center.} 
10. Nxe5 {This is more or less an only move already, but some very strong players have gone astray here. I think Black's position is not easy to play.} 
11. dxe5 {Now, historically the main move here has been to retreat the knight to d7. I actually think this is much less challenging than if it goes to d5.} 
11. Nd5 {I am very convinced that this is the best move. The knight on d7 feels dumb to me since Black never really gets to take on e5 anyway. Not only is it more active on d5, but it also plugs the long diagonal and makes it easier for Black to execute the c6-c5 break.} 
12. Nc3 {As usual, White's top priority needs to be preventing c6-c5. Pressuring the knight is a good way to do that.} 
12. Be7 {This is Black's best move. He knows he will have to make it at some point, can castle next, and someday bring his queen to either b8 or c7 to prepare for Nd5xc3 and c6-c5.} 
13. Rd1 {Now, White is threatening e2-e4, forcing Black to move his queen.} 
13. Qc7 {13...O-O?14.e4+-White wins a piece.13...Qb814.Nxd5cxd515.Be3This leads to a similar position to the mainline.} 
14. Nxd5 {Sadly, I think we have to accept symmetry here.} 
14. cxd5 {Black is arguing that our rook coming to d1 was something of a wasted tempo, and he is claiming that once he castles and starts bringing rooks to the c-file, he should be able to trade a bunch of stuff and be basically fine. There is no doubt, this position is pretty thin for White, but I don't think Black can claim full equality just yet.14...exd5?!Black will regret trying to get creative.15.e4!White is blowing up the center and Black has to be precise not to lose right away.} 
15. Be3
15. O-O
16. Rac1
16. Qxe5 {It's quite nice that this does not work so well. Still, it is a natural move that White should be ready for, since precision is required.} 
17. Bf4
17. Qf6
18. Rc7 {White's pieces are springing to life. It is a very bad sign for Black that the machine wants him to play Bb7-c8.} 
18. Rab8 {This feels like the human move to me. White should be precise.} 
19. h4 {The threat of Bf4-g5 is rather obvious. I struggle to imagine a human being not pushing h7-h6 in response.} 
19. h6
20. Qe3 {Now we follow a forced line. The threat of Bf4-e5 forces Be7-d8.} 
20. Bd8
21. Rd7
21. Bc6
22. Bxb8
22. Bxd7
23. Bd6
23. Be7 {23...Re8?I could see a human playing like this.24.Qa7!Bc825.Rc1±Black is facing serious problems on the queenside.} 
24. Bxe7
24. Qxe7
25. Bxd5 {Black still has some problems to solve and his position is a bit loose. He cannot bring the rook to c8 too easily with Bd5-b7 hanging over his head, his queenside pawns may end up fixed on light squares, and once White retreats the bishop from d5, it will not be totally trivial to prevent Qe3-a7.} 
