15. Be3
15. O-O
16. Rac1
16. Qd7
17. Be4 {I like this move, aiming to transfer the otherwise passive-looking bishop to b1. White will set up with Be3-d4, Qb3-e3, and then start pushing kingside pawns.   Black is probably more or less okay, but his position still feels a little uncomfortable to me, and there are some long-term strategic dangers thanks to his bad bishop on b7 and White's extra space from the e5-pawn.   We will see a fantastic game from a young Nils Grandelius in a similar position in the annotated games section.} 
