7. c5 {This is a very important move. Black takes some share of the center, making it harder to push d2-d4, but more importantly, he is threatening to play b7-b5 again. White will lack a dangerous discovery with the knight, as bringing it to c6 will no longer be a winning proposition.7...Be7?A simple developing move like this one leaves Black in horrible shape. Following8.O-Ohe now will absolutely never be able to push his b-pawn, as a knight landing on c6 will be devastating. And otherwise, how else can he hope to develop his queenside?} 
8. Nc3 {A very important move, serving as prophylaxis against b7-b5. Now, if White's knight on f3 moves to create a discovered attack, Black will not be able to block with Nf6-d5.8.O-O?It might be tempting to castle, but this allows Black to show his idea.8...b5!Sadly, White no longer has a dangerous discovery with the knight on f3. The big point is that once it lands on c6, Black's queen has the c7-square.} 
8. Qc7 {Another important move. Black's hope is to finally play b7-b5 next, when he can meet a knight discovery with Bc8-b7.} 
9. d4 {Castling is also possible and used to be the main move, but I think it is an interesting new direction. White makes sure to be ready for Bc1-f4 at a moment before Black can respond with Bf8-d6. I also like that it keeps this chapter consistent - at every moment that Black plays Qd8-c7, we are always responding with d2-d4.9.O-OFor a long time, this was considered the main move. It is a decent option, but I dislike that after9...b610.d4Bb711.Bf4Black is able to play Bf8-d6, rather than losing more time with his queen.} 
9. b5 {Finally, Black executes his plan. He had plenty of opportunities to go wrong up to this point, and now he managed to avoid the numerous pitfalls and get the b7-b5 advance in. Thematically, once the bishop comes to b7, Black should be totally fine, but now White can hope to make use of a growing lead in development by hitting the queen on c7 with a gain of tempo.} 
10. Bf4 {Now, it feels incredibly natural to play Bf8-d6 to try not to fall too far behind on development, but this is actually a mistake.} 
10. Qb6 {This feels more natural to me. I think Black can survive, but it requires extremely precise play deep into the middlegame and well past the present state of opening theory.} 
11. Ne5 {As we have seen so many previous times, White meets Qc7-b6 with Nf3-e5.} 
11. Bb7
12. Nxd7
12. Nxd7
13. d5 {Now, at this moment, Black's position is quite dangerous strategically. If he were to play Bf8-e7, he would quickly transpose to something we have already covered and know to be good for White. But, by not playing Bf8-e7 so fast, he has an important resource.} 
13. Nf6 {Black attacks the d5-pawn before White has castled. This means that White cannot respond with a move like d5xe6 or d5-d6.13...Be7?We have seen this before.14.O-O±White has a fantastic position with Rf1-d1 and e2-e4 on the way.} 
14. e4
14. c4 {A very important move, and the crux of Black's plan. By waiting on developing his bishop, he now can put it on the much more active c5-square. Not only is it better placed there for active purposes, but it also will not run into any d5-d6 tricks.} 
15. O-O-O {Given that Black has set up his pieces in a way that guarantees him a reasonable position strategically, White's best chance to fight for an edge revolves around trying to maximize his lead in development as efficiently as possible. Black still needs to be very precise to hang on here.} 
15. Bc5 {This move is not too hard- especially given Black had the foresight to push c5-c4 instead of continuing with simple development, I don't really see him playing something else.15...Be716.d6!Bd817.Be3With f2-f4 coming next, I would not want to be Black here.} 
16. dxe6 {White takes on e6, forcing Black to take back with the pawn.} 
16. fxe6 {Now, Black is ready to castle next, with a very harmonious position. We have to be fast and get to the point.} 
17. e5 {White starts tactical operations, making use of his lead in development. Black has to walk a tightrope to survive.} 
17. Bxg2 {17...Nd718.Ne4!±Black will struggle to castle thanks to the loose knight on d7, and he just looks worse to me. White's pieces are very active.} 
18. exf6
18. gxf6 {This feels like the human move to me, but it basically loses.} 
19. Rhe1 {Black's king is stuck in the center, and he will face a vicious attack.} 
19. Rd8 {The machine claims this is the only move not to lose immediately. Still, Black's position is miserable.} 
20. Ne4
20. Bd4
21. Nd6+
21. Rxd6
22. Bxd6
22. Qxd6
23. Qd2 {White wins the bishop on d4, since e6-e5 does not actually save it thanks to the pin on the e-file. Black is still fighting and can trade queens and get his bishop to d5, so it will take some work to win the game, but the extra material is still really nice.} 
