6. a6 {And we see Black's point. He is hoping to execute strategy 2. He took on c4, and he did not manage to hang onto the pawn. But, he is hoping that by dragging White's queen to c4 and costing her tempi in the meantime, he can play b7-b5 next with a gain of tempo and then get his bishop to b7 before allowing White's knight on f3 to move with an unpleasant discovery. White should be precise.6...Be7?This move might look natural enough, but it completely underestimates the strategic danger in Black's position. If he is not able to develop his bishop to b7, soon, his queenside can become permanently stuck.} 
7. Qc2 {A very important move. White's queen clearly could not remain on c4 and had to move anyway, but by bringing her back directly, Black is now unable to push b7-b5. He has to react very precisely here, since he will be more or less completely lost if he cannot get his bishop to b7.   The whole struggle will revolve around the b7-b5 advance. If White can prevent it completely, Black is done for. If Black gets it in without any incident, he will immediately equalize, and in my opinion, he will have a more pleasant position thanks to the extra space from the pawn on c5. But, the natural middle ground if both sides play well is that Black will be able to get this move in, but only at a cost.7.d4?This is a mistake, and it highlights why the 1. d4 move order gives Black a lot of extra options in the Catalan. Black gets his bishop to b7 and is absolutely fine.7...b5=7.Qb3Placing the queen on the same square as we would against the 6... c5 line does not work as well. After7...Rb8!We cannot prevent b7-b5 from coming next, and the pawn remaining on c7 means that White can't make any trouble with Bc1-f4.} 
7. c5 {This is a very important move. Black takes some share of the center, making it harder to push d2-d4, but more importantly, he is threatening to play b7-b5 again. White will lack a dangerous discovery with the knight, as bringing it to c6 will no longer be a winning proposition.7...Be7?A simple developing move like this one leaves Black in horrible shape. Following8.O-Ohe now will absolutely never be able to push his b-pawn, as a knight landing on c6 will be devastating. And otherwise, how else can he hope to develop his queenside?} 
8. Nc3 {A very important move, serving as prophylaxis against b7-b5. Now, if White's knight on f3 moves to create a discovered attack, Black will not be able to block with Nf6-d5.8.O-O?It might be tempting to castle, but this allows Black to show his idea.8...b5!Sadly, White no longer has a dangerous discovery with the knight on f3. The big point is that once it lands on c6, Black's queen has the c7-square.} 
8. Qc7 {Another important move. Black's hope is to finally play b7-b5 next, when he can meet a knight discovery with Bc8-b7.} 
9. d4 {Castling is also possible and used to be the main move, but I think it is an interesting new direction. White makes sure to be ready for Bc1-f4 at a moment before Black can respond with Bf8-d6. I also like that it keeps this chapter consistent - at every moment that Black plays Qd8-c7, we are always responding with d2-d4.9.O-OFor a long time, this was considered the main move. It is a decent option, but I dislike that after9...b610.d4Bb711.Bf4Black is able to play Bf8-d6, rather than losing more time with his queen.} 
9. b5 {Finally, Black executes his plan. He had plenty of opportunities to go wrong up to this point, and now he managed to avoid the numerous pitfalls and get the b7-b5 advance in. Thematically, once the bishop comes to b7, Black should be totally fine, but now White can hope to make use of a growing lead in development by hitting the queen on c7 with a gain of tempo.} 
10. Bf4 {Now, it feels incredibly natural to play Bf8-d6 to try not to fall too far behind on development, but this is actually a mistake.} 
10. Qa7 {This is surely the best move, and a very hard one for an unprepared player to choose. The queen looks really off on a7, but the point is that after Nf3-e5, he can safely play Bc8-b7 and the queen will not be attacked by Ne5xd7.} 
11. d5 {White should absolutely be aiming to make use of his big lead in development. Black's position would be fine if he had time to play Bc8-b7. Now, I do believe Black survives here, but it takes some very precise play. It's also nice that this position has only seen play twice before, both games from the 1960s! It is very fresh stuff.} 
11. Nxd5 {This is the only move to not lose immediately. By exchanging the knights, Black does a better job of keeping the center closed.} 
12. Nxd5
12. exd5 {Now, Black is a pawn up and has a massive center. Should he complete his development, he will just be better. But, that is a big if.} 
13. O-O
13. Bb7 {I could see a human doing this, but it is a serious mistake. Every tempo not spent on evacuating the king is asking for trouble.} 
14. a4
14. Be7 {Black probably should play this to go into damage control mode.} 
15. axb5
15. Qb6
16. bxa6
16. Rxa6
17. Bh3 {White should be slightly better thanks to his potential to play against the hanging pawns, and Bg2-h3 will put annoying pressure on the d7-knight and make it hard to castle. But Black is not dead or anything.} 
