4. dxc4 {This is Black's last reasonable opportunity to try to capture on c4.} 
5. Qa4+ {White takes back the pawn on c4 without allowing Black to attempt to defend it. Now, Black has a few options of how to get his pieces out.} 
5. Nbd7 {Thematically, this feels like the most principled move, and I believe it is the strongest one. Black brings out a new piece and does not block the long diagonal.} 
6. Qxc4 {Now, Black only has two serious moves.} 
6. a6 {And we see Black's point. He is hoping to execute strategy 2. He took on c4, and he did not manage to hang onto the pawn. But, he is hoping that by dragging White's queen to c4 and costing her tempi in the meantime, he can play b7-b5 next with a gain of tempo and then get his bishop to b7 before allowing White's knight on f3 to move with an unpleasant discovery. White should be precise.6...Be7?This move might look natural enough, but it completely underestimates the strategic danger in Black's position. If he is not able to develop his bishop to b7, soon, his queenside can become permanently stuck.} 
7. Qc2 {A very important move. White's queen clearly could not remain on c4 and had to move anyway, but by bringing her back directly, Black is now unable to push b7-b5. He has to react very precisely here, since he will be more or less completely lost if he cannot get his bishop to b7.   The whole struggle will revolve around the b7-b5 advance. If White can prevent it completely, Black is done for. If Black gets it in without any incident, he will immediately equalize, and in my opinion, he will have a more pleasant position thanks to the extra space from the pawn on c5. But, the natural middle ground if both sides play well is that Black will be able to get this move in, but only at a cost.7.d4?This is a mistake, and it highlights why the 1. d4 move order gives Black a lot of extra options in the Catalan. Black gets his bishop to b7 and is absolutely fine.7...b5=7.Qb3Placing the queen on the same square as we would against the 6... c5 line does not work as well. After7...Rb8!We cannot prevent b7-b5 from coming next, and the pawn remaining on c7 means that White can't make any trouble with Bc1-f4.} 
7. c5 {This is a very important move. Black takes some share of the center, making it harder to push d2-d4, but more importantly, he is threatening to play b7-b5 again. White will lack a dangerous discovery with the knight, as bringing it to c6 will no longer be a winning proposition.7...Be7?A simple developing move like this one leaves Black in horrible shape. Following8.O-Ohe now will absolutely never be able to push his b-pawn, as a knight landing on c6 will be devastating. And otherwise, how else can he hope to develop his queenside?} 
