[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction to setups with ...c6 and ...d5"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6 {By choosing 1... c6 on the first move of the game, Black clearly wishes to push d7-d5 next and take the game into Slav territory. Much like we see in the 1... e6 lines, White's best hope at claiming an opening advantage lies in trying to make the g2 bishop better than its counterpart on c8. Broadly speaking, Black has two strategies he can execute to try to equalize.   The first strategy Black can attempt is to make use of delaying e7-e6, get the bishop outside of the pawn chain, and then push e7-e6 later, playing some kind of reversed Torre or London system. Should he pull this off, he can make a fair case that his bishop will be no worse than its counterpart on g2. In general, I find this unconvincing for him. We can make good use of avoiding the d2-d4 advance, mainly by placing the pawn on d3 instead to restrict Black's bishop, but also by sparing a tempo in touching the d-pawn and instead aiming for direct hostilities with Qd1-b3 as soon as Black's bishops leaves the defense of the b7-pawn.   The second strategy is to take the pawn on c4 and hang on to it. This is a much more feasible option here than it would be in a 1... e6 move order because White does not have an immediate check on a4 to take back the missing pawn. This is what I recommended in my own repertoire here on Chessable when covering the English, and I think it is the most critical spot in the entire course, as actually taking material from us and attempting to keep it is a very ambitious thing to do, and the lines generally seem sound for Black if he is well prepared.   As such, I have decided to make the c6 and d5 section the final one of the course. Still, while I consider it to be our toughest test, I believe I can put some pressure on Black's position and challenge the current state of theory to some degree.} 
2. g3
2. d5 {2...e5This will transpose to the 1... e5 lines, which will be covered in the second course.} 
3. Nf3 {Of course, we do not allow Black to take the entire center with e7-e5 as well as d7-d5. Now, Black can consider any of Bc8-f5, Bc8-g4, ...d5xc4, or g7-g6. He can do this both at this moment directly, or with the moves Ng8-f6 and Bf1-g2 included. White's best attempt to fight for the advantage revolves around not allowing Black to execute any of these strategies effectively.•3.Bg2?!e5!Black takes the whole center. This we wish to avoid.} 
3. Nf6 {•3...Bf5Against Bc8-f5, we generally want to respond by putting our queen on b3.4.Qb3•3...Bg4The bishop tends to be better on g4 than f5. I really don't want to allow Black to play Bc8-g4 and e7-e6- then I think he gets a solid, playable position. We always meet Bc8-g4 with Nf3-e5.4.Ne5!} 
4. Bg2
4. dxc4 {•4...Bf55.Qb3!•4...Bg45.Ne5!Here as well, we meet Bc8-g4 with Nf3-e5.•4...e65.b3transposes to Chapter 4.} 
5. O-O {Now, Black has several ways to try to hang on to the pawn. We should be precise and careful to not only get the pawn back, but also prevent Black from making too much progress while we are busy equalizing material.} 
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Setups with c6/d5, Black plays w/o ...dxc4 "]
[Black "c6/d5 Setups: 3...Bg4 4.Ne5 Be6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3
3. Bg4 {In general, I think that trying to develop the bishop outside of the pawn chain and pushing e7-e6 next is not Black's best attempt to fight for equality, and it all comes down to our decision to play the English. In general, I believe White's d-pawn will be much better placed on d3 than d4, and that he can use that to play against Black's light-squared bishop. Still, if this is the plan Black decides he wants to execute, I think it is much better to do it now than it would be to include Ng8-f6 and Bf1-g2 first.} 
4. Ne5 {I like this very direct move. Black should not be easily allowed to get the bishop outside of the pawn chain and push e7-e6, as then he will be able to take back on d5 with the pawn. Now, Black has tried both ...Be6 and ...Bf5 an equal number of times, but in my opinion, ...Bf5 is a much stronger move.} 
4. Be6 {This move looks pretty dumb to me. There do exist lines where Black wants the bishop on e6, but they mainly involve grabbing the c4-pawn early. Here it just looks misplaced.} 
5. d4 {White grabs the whole center and need not fear d5xc4. He is ready to take on d5 next.} 
5. dxc4
6. e4 {White wins his pawn back with a fantastic position thanks to his extra space in the center. He can develop with Bf1xc4, Nb1-c3, Bc1-e3, and O-O.} 
6. b5 {Black should probably make a quieter move like g7-g6, but he is undeniably worse there against a simple plan. However, it is nice to know that attempting to keep the extra material falls on its face.} 
7. a4 {Simple and totally devastating. White is ready for a4xb5 and Nb1-c3 to follow, and the machine claims Black is done for already.} 
