[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3
3. Bg4 {In general, I think that trying to develop the bishop outside of the pawn chain and pushing e7-e6 next is not Black's best attempt to fight for equality, and it all comes down to our decision to play the English. In general, I believe White's d-pawn will be much better placed on d3 than d4, and that he can use that to play against Black's light-squared bishop. Still, if this is the plan Black decides he wants to execute, I think it is much better to do it now than it would be to include Ng8-f6 and Bf1-g2 first.} 
4. Ne5 {I like this very direct move. Black should not be easily allowed to get the bishop outside of the pawn chain and push e7-e6, as then he will be able to take back on d5 with the pawn. Now, Black has tried both ...Be6 and ...Bf5 an equal number of times, but in my opinion, ...Bf5 is a much stronger move.} 
4. Bf5 {I am quite confident that this is the best move. Black could also play this exact same position with White's knight back on f3 by playing Bc8-f5 rather than stopping on g4 first, but with the knight on e5, Black can hope for f7-f6 and to claim that it is overextended. Still, I think White can try to make use of Black losing some time.} 
5. Qb3 {White pressures the b7-pawn. Black should be precise here.} 
5. Qb6 {This move should be second nature to a Slav player, but the present position should also make him pause. After all, White can now take on b6 and then d5, when Black will have to take back with the c-pawn. This is something Black surely wants to avoid.   Additionally, cxd5 directly, which is my recommendation, looks very venomous and Black should be super careful. Although I do believe this is best, it is much less common than Nb8-d7 instead, which surely fails to equalize.} 
6. cxd5 {I like this option a lot. Black now needs to find a few very difficult moves (no human has found them yet, at least not in OTB chess) to reach a roughly even endgame that I would still prefer the white side of.6.Qxb6This move looks very scary for Black, and in order to go for this line, he has to realize that following6...axb67.cxd5Be4!He is able to take back on d5 with the bishop rather than the pawn, though even this position is playable for White.} 
6. Qxb3 {Otherwise Black loses a pawn.} 
7. axb3 {Now, Black has to find a very difficult only move to even stay in the game. In the four times this position has seen play, no Black player has found it.} 
7. Be4 {This has been the most common move in practice, but it falls prey to a very pretty tactic.} 
8. dxc6
8. Bxh1 {8...Nxc6This is relatively best, but after the simple9.f3!±White is a clean pawn up and basically winning.} 
9. Rxa7 {It's rare to see romantic shots like this in modern-era chess, particularly within 1. c4 openings! Black can resign. Taking the rook allows c6-c7.} 
