5. e5 {This position is very common, and known to be quite fine for Black, when the moves c2-c4 and c7-c6 are not included. He may be fine here as well, but I am not entirely convinced.5...Nf66.b3!This transposes to the g6 chapter.} 
6. d3
6. Ne7
7. e4 {White starts to pressure Black's center. The pawn on c6 denies Black's knight access to the c6-square, which makes it much harder for him to fight for equality.} 
7. dxc4
8. dxc4
8. Qxd1
9. Rxd1 {I have played this endgame several times with the pawns back on c2 and c6, and I think Black is basically fine. Here, the inability to put the knight on c6 means his development is really lagging, and White has nice squares for all of his pieces. He should be a bit better.} 
