7. e4 {White starts to pressure Black's center. The pawn on c6 denies Black's knight access to the c6-square, which makes it much harder for him to fight for equality.} 
7. O-O {7...d48.b4!Black has nothing better than castling, transposing to the mainline.} 
8. b4 {I like this move a lot, gaining queenside space and further highlighting that Black is missing Nb8-c6. White is ready to push a2-a4 next with Bc1-a3 to follow.} 
8. d4 {My machine insists this is best, but I think it underestimates the practical danger to Black's position.8...b69.a4The threat of b4-b5 means that Black cannot really maintain the tension anymore, and the machine now insists that he must push d5-d4, reaching a similar position to the mainline.} 
9. a4
9. c5
10. b5 {Despite silicon's insistence upon equality, I actually think this position is very difficult for Black. White's point is very simple. He is playing a reversed King's Indian where his pawn advances mean that Black will not be able to open the queenside in an effective way. White continues with Bc1-d2, Nb1-a3 to keep the queenside forever secure, and someday plays Nh4 or Ne1 and sends the f-pawn, starting a typical King's Indian attack.} 
