2. d5
3. Nf3
3. Nf6 {This move is generally considered to be pretty automatic, but Black does have some extra options afforded to him by delaying it.} 
4. Bg2
4. Nbd7 {This move has been seen before, but it is not too scary to me. White can certainly push d2-d4 to take the game back into a good version of the Slav where Black missed his chance to play Bc8-f5, but I see no reason to go back into 1. d4 land just yet.4...e65.b3is covered in the 1... e6 section.} 
5. O-O {Black should probably take on c4, leading to position we will see in the next chapter, but he does have a couple extra options.} 
5. e5 {Taking the whole center like this is very ambitious, but it's hard to believe it will work with the knight on d7 disturbing Black's coordination.5...e66.b3transposes back towards the positions we see in the 1... e6 section.} 
6. d4
6. e4
7. Ne5
7. Be7 {Black can also develop the bishop more modestly. He still should be worse, but we need to treat the position differently.} 
8. cxd5
8. cxd5
9. Nc3
9. O-O
10. f3 {Since we managed to keep our knight on e5, Black is unable to use the e-file to defend his e4-pawn, and he will have to take on f3.} 
10. exf3
11. exf3 {White is ready for f3-f4 next. The machine is not that impressed with his position, but I think it looks very uncomfortable for Black. The e5-knight is fantastic and the c8-bishop will struggle to develop.} 
