3. dxc4 {Unlike what we saw in the lines with 1... e6, now White cannot simply recapture on c4. The upside for Black is that there is some potential for him to remain a pawn up, but the upside for White is that if he is able to take back the missing pawn, he should have a huge position because c7-c6 is totally out of place when considering the plan of bringing the c8-bishop to the long diagonal to neutralize the beast on g2.3...Nf64.Bg2Now, taking on c4 transposes to the mainline in this chapter, while any other move is covered in the previous section.} 
4. Bg2 {Now, the main move by far is Ng8-f6, for obvious reasons. But, Black does have some extraneous options as well. One rule of thumb here is that White should be trying to take back on c4, but if Black ever pushes b7-b5, just give up on that plan. You will not get your pawn back, but you will have good attacking chances.} 
4. b5 {This is way too ambitious. In general, whenever Black plays b7-b5, we have to just accept that we will not get our pawn back and play for the initiative instead, aiming to open lines with moves like d2-d3 or a2-a4 while Black is not developing his pieces.   As such, I think it almost never makes any sense at all for Black to play b7-b5 without first waiting for White to actually spend a tempo attacking the c4-pawn with a move like Qd1-c2. Furthermore, this plan makes a lot less sense for Black than it would in a proper Catalan from a 1. d4 move order since White has the additional pawn break d2-d3 available- something I wish to make use of!} 
5. O-O
5. Bb7
6. a4
6. e6 {6...a67.d3!cxd38.Ne5!Black faces similar problems that he sees in the mainline.} 
7. d3 {A position like this perfectly highlights why I believe b7-b5 was ill-advised when Black played it. He more or less has to take on d3, trading off his potentially weak pawn to remain a pawn up. But then, White is very happy to have not burned a tempo on Qd1-c2.} 
7. cxd3 {Now, there is no time to be a wimp. Taking back one of the two lost pawns and butchering your own structure with a move like exd3 leaves you with a horrible position, and White should be very aggressive.} 
8. Ne5 {Now, White is threatening to take on b5, with immediate devastation.} 
8. a6
9. Qxd3
9. Qxd3
10. Nxd3 {White's compensation remains well into the endgame, and Black is hard pressed to stop a total disaster on either c5 or a5 once the b1-knight reaches b3.} 
