[Black "c6/d5 Setups: 4...Nf6 5.O-O Nbd7 with 7...Be6 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3 {In the previous section, we saw some of Black's attempts to get his bishop outside the pawn chain before pushing e7-e6. Here, we will examine the most direct strategy of all- taking the c4-pawn and trying to hang on to it.} 
3. dxc4 {Unlike what we saw in the lines with 1... e6, now White cannot simply recapture on c4. The upside for Black is that there is some potential for him to remain a pawn up, but the upside for White is that if he is able to take back the missing pawn, he should have a huge position because c7-c6 is totally out of place when considering the plan of bringing the c8-bishop to the long diagonal to neutralize the beast on g2.3...Nf64.Bg2Now, taking on c4 transposes to the mainline in this chapter, while any other move is covered in the previous section.} 
4. Bg2 {Now, the main move by far is Ng8-f6, for obvious reasons. But, Black does have some extraneous options as well. One rule of thumb here is that White should be trying to take back on c4, but if Black ever pushes b7-b5, just give up on that plan. You will not get your pawn back, but you will have good attacking chances.} 
4. Nf6
5. O-O
5. Nbd7 {This is surely Black's best attempt at fighting for equality, and my own recommendation for Black in my Black vs the English, Reti, and Sidelines course. I stand by the work I did there, and I think in a higher chess sense, Black is definitely fine, but I can apply some practical pressure from the White side as well.•5...e66.a4transposes to the 4... e6 line.•5...Be66.Qc2Black has nothing better than ...Nbd7 here, which will transpose to the 5... Nbd7 lines.6...Nbd77.Na3Nb68.Ne5transposes to the mainline.} 
6. Qc2
6. Nb6 {Still following my recommendation.} 
7. Na3 {With Black, I wrote that Black should try to hang onto the c4-pawn if White does not play a2-a4, and that he should not try to if White does and instead play against the weakened b4-square. In general, I think White should be trying to make the most strategically sound moves he can to apply maximum pressure, and I like not including a2-a4.7.a4It is also possible to include a2-a4 and a7-a5, but I don't like them as much.7...a58.Na3The big reason that I am not sold on this for White is that I think a knight coming to b4 will be very annoying, and I am not convinced that White is better if Black simply gives back the pawn.8...g69.Nxc4Nxc410.Qxc4Bg7With ...O-O, ...Be6, and Nf6-d5-b4 potentially coming, I don't think White is any better. The last part of that equation is critical in Black's claim to full equality, and I really dislike the inclusion of a2-a4 and a7-a5.} 
7. Be6 {Black should be fighting to hang on to the pawn. We have seen this position before without O-O and Ng8-f6 included, and there I quite liked the bold advance Nf3-g5. In the present position, that can be well met with Be6-g4, and I think I made a very strong case that Black should be fine. White has a couple options, but I like immediately taking back the lost pawn.} 
8. Ne5 {White is very direct and looks to take back the lost pawn on c4. Should he manage to do this without incident, I believe he will be better. Black should try not to make it so easy for him. Historically, the main move has been Qd8-d4, aiming to hold the pawn. But, in the last two years, the counterattacking move h7-h5 exploded in popularity. Of course, this has absolutely nothing to do with my recommending the move in my English Reti and Sidelines course at precisely that moment! We must take both moves very seriously.8.Ng5Bg4!I think Black is fine here. You can still play it and there are some ideas to explore, but I prefer Nf3-e5 instead.8.b3cxb39.axb3White surely has compensation for the missing pawn here and the position is fully playable, but I find it much less convincing than what we had in a previous line where we got to take the e6-bishop with the f3-knight. Without the bishop pair, and with our knight on f3 not being the world's best piece, I think Black is very fine.} 
8. Qd4 {The old main move is very logical. What could be more natural than saving the attacked pawn and developing a new piece with tempo? There is no time to good around and White must spring into action right away.} 
9. Nxc6 {The fireworks begin.} 
9. bxc6
10. Bxc6+
10. Bd7
11. Bxa8
11. Nxa8 {Now we see why the bishop was missing on e6.} 
12. Nxc4 {I prefer White in this somewhat unusual position. He is ready for d2-d3 or b2-b3 next, when he will get his c1-bishop out with a gain of tempo and quickly take the c-file. Normally, 2 pieces are better than a rook and 2 pawns in the middlegame, but this is a different story.   The biggest problem Black is facing is that his absence of d and b-pawns makes a lot of squares on his c-file very vulnerable, and for once, the rooks will look like very good pieces even in the early middlegame.} 
