12. Bxa8 {Now, in practice, Black has mainly taken on b5 here. I actually think Nxa8 is the better move, but it takes a ton of precision from Black that no humans have shown yet.} 
12. Qxb5 {This is the main move, but I really like that our light squared bishop got to stay alive.} 
13. Bg2 {Now, Black should be extremely precise. If he does not play the best move, he will be much worse. White's plan is simple- kick the queen with a2-a4 and blow up the center with d2-d3.} 
13. Bd7 {This has only been seen once before, but it was from a game in the candidates. As such, I have to believe this move is reasonably well known at the super-GM level if Black plays this line, but beneath that, I would not count on it. Black prevents a2-a4 and gets ready for e7-e5, and he now also does not have to worry as much about d2-d3 since he can take it without Rf1-d1 as a possibility.13...h5?This has been the most common move so far, but it is rather terrible.14.a4!±White blows up the center with d2-d3 next and is close to winning already.} 
14. Rd1 {White has other moves but I think this is his best try. It is not even remotely subtle and Black should be very precise to hang on.} 
14. Qa4 {It feels much more natural to me for Black to want to get the queens off right away, when in fact he really should wait on this move.} 
15. Qxa4
15. Bxa4
16. b3
16. cxb3
17. axb3
17. Bxb3
18. Re1 {White has not committed to d2-d3 yet, and will put the pawn on d4 instead, stopping e7-e5. Black definitely has a lot more problems to solve here than he does in the mainline.} 
