15. Qc2 {As mentioned, the queen was better on c2 than c3. So, White accepts the loss of a tempo to bring her back. He still has a very straightforward and dangerous plan of Rf1-d1 and Bc1-f4. The machine claims Black is in huge trouble if he does not take on d4.} 
15. Qxd4
16. Bf4 {With white to play, this position was absolutely winning. But a tempo in such a sharp position is a big deal, and the computer claims Black is basically fine. Still, I think there are some very real practical chances and would surely prefer the White side in human play. He will follow up with Rf1-d1 and can even consider throwing b2-b4-b5 in some cases.   Usually, when you go deep enough in a solid mainline opening, you ultimately reach a position that feels a bit more comfortable for White in practice, but also objectively should not be a clean advantage or anything like that.   This is what we have here. I was actually very glad to see how well my English, Reti, and sidelines course held up over the last 2 years - even with much newer and much more powerful engines now than what we had then, I am glad that this is the best I could find for White.} 
